(36, 'vt10219', 1, 'INNO-Q-NOL™ Carnitine', 'CoQ10 Ubiquinol with patented Q-Nol® for extended shelf life ', 'Includes L-Carnitine to boost metabolism', '<p>While every cell in the body requires Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10) to produce energy, the cells in the heart require some of the most significant amounts.&nbsp; Clinical studies have shown that CoQ10 can reduce the risk for cardiovascular problems. INNO-Q-NOL Carnitine with Ubiquinol CoQ10 restores these antioxicant levels to support cardiovascular health but also&nbsp; includes L-carnitine,&nbsp; &nbsp;an amino acid (a building block for proteins) that is naturally produced in the body and&nbsp; helps the body turn fat into energy.</p>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\">Key Benefits:</span></h5>\n<ul>\n<li>Reduce the risk for cardiovascular disease</li>\n<li>Boost energy levels</li>\n<li>Provide antioxidant protection &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Formulated with a highly absorbable and stable form of L-carnitine, &nbsp;a substance that helps the body turn fat into energy</li>\n<li>Clinically studied formulation that has shown to provide significant improvements in cardiovascular health</li>\n</ul>\n<h5>The INNO-Q-NOL CoQ10 Family</h5>\n<p>Powered by the patented&nbsp; Q-Nol&reg; process (US Patent 6,740,338) which ensures  ubiquinol in the finished product stays stable (i.e. as ubiquinol)  through to product expiration, the INNO-Q-Nol family of products also includes INNO-Q-NOL and INNO-Q-NOL Blood Pressure.</p>', '<p>This  year, heart disease will affect more women in Canada than any other  disease.&nbsp; Cardiovascular afflictions can include atherosclerosis, hypertension, stroke and heart attack.</p>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\" lang=\\"EN\\">About CoQ10</span><span lang=\\"EN\\">&nbsp;</span></h5>\n<p><span lang=\\"EN\\">Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10) is an extremely important nutrient that every cell in your body must have in order to produce energy. It is naturally found in the energy-producing center of the cell known as the mitochondria, the part of a cell responsible for the production of energy in the form of ATP (Adenosine triphosphate). ATP serves as the cell\\''s major energy source and drives a number of biological processes, including muscle contraction and the production of protein. CoQ10 is involved in making this important molecule.</span></p>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\" lang=\\"EN\\">Ubiquinone vs. Ubiquinol</span><span lang=\\"EN\\">&nbsp;</span></h5>\n<p><span lang=\\"EN\\">Ubiquinone is the standard form of CoQ10. The body must automatically convert ubiquinone to ubiquinol - the most body-ready form of CoQ10 - to help in cell energy production by providing quick and efficient replenishment.&nbsp; Aging inhibits this conversion process hence the requirement for CoQ10 supplementation, where the body-ready ubiquinol form may achieve the most optimal benefits. Human clinical studies have shown that when compared to standard CoQ10 supplements ubiquinol is: 8x better absorbed in the bloodstream; reduces exercise-induced fatigue by 90%; and slows aging by 40%.</span></p>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\" lang=\\"EN\\">Ubiquinol with Q-Nol&reg; stability</span><span lang=\\"EN\\">&nbsp;</span></h5>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\" lang=\\"EN\\">Stabilized ubiquinol from ingredient to product expiration</span><span lang=\\"EN\\">&nbsp;</span></h5>\n<p><span lang=\\"EN\\">&nbsp;</span><span lang=\\"EN\\">Ubiquinol by nature is not stable (i.e. reverts back to ubiquinone). To ensure the superior efficacy of ubiquinol at the time of ingestion, Innovite Health&nbsp; utilizes one additional manufacturing step, the patented&nbsp; Q-Nol&reg; process (US Patent 6,740,338) which ensures ubiquinol in the finished product stays stable (i.e. as ubiquinol) through to product expiration.</span></p>\n<h5><span class=\\"bold\\">About L-carnitine</span></h5>\n<p>L-carnitine is an amino acid (a building block for proteins) that is naturally produced in the body and&nbsp; helps the body turn fat into energy. The body produces it in the liver and kidneys and stores it in the skeletal muscles, heart, brain, and sperm.&nbsp;Some people, however, may not have enough carnitine because their bodies cannot make enough or can&rsquo;t transport it into tissues so it can be used. It has been proposed as a treatment for many conditions because it acts as an antioxidant. Antioxidants fight harmful particles in the body known as free radicals, which damage cells and tamper with DNA. Antioxidants can neutralize free radicals and may reduce or help prevent some of the damage they cause.</p>\n<h5>Sources:</h5>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0273230006001322\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><span style=\\"mso-ansi-language: EN;\\" lang=\\"EN\\">Hosoe  K, Kitano M, Kishida H, Kubo H, Fujii K, Kitahara M. Study on safety  and bioavailability of ubiquinol (Kaneka QH) after single and 4-week  multiple oral administration to healthy volunteers.</span><span lang=\\"EN\\"> </span></a><span style=\\"mso-ansi-language: EN;\\" lang=\\"EN\\"><a href=\\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0273230006001322\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Regul Toxicol Pharmacol. 2007 Feb;47(1):19-28. Epub 2006 Aug 21</a>. </span></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0273230006001322\\"></a><a href=\\"http://www.nrjournal.com/article/S0271-5317(02)00402-5/abstract\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Michael  V Miles, Paul Horn, Lili Miles, Peter Tang, Paul Steele, Ton DeGrauw.  Bioequivalence of coenzyme Q10 from over-the-counter supplements. Nutr  Res. Aug 2002;22(8):919-929. </a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><span style=\\"mso-spacerun: yes;\\">&nbsp;</span><a href=\\"http://acb.rsmjournals.com/cgi/content/abstract/40/1/100\\" target=\\"_blank\\"><span style=\\"mso-ansi-language: EN;\\" lang=\\"EN\\">Hectors MP et al. Stability studies of ubiquinol in plasma. Ann Clin Biochem. 2003 Jan;40(Pt 1):100-1.</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\\"http://www.medsci.org/v09p0621.htm\\" target=\\"_blank\\">Kaya  Y, et al. Correlations between oxidative DNA damage, oxidative stress  and coenzyme Q10 in patients with coronary artery disease. Int J Med  Sci. 2012;9(8):621-6. Epub 2012 Sep 19.</a></li>\n<li><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:WordDocument> <w:View>Normal</w:View> <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom> <w:TrackMoves /> <w:TrackFormatting /> <w:PunctuationKerning /> <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas /> <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid> <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent> <w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText>false</w:AlwaysShowPlaceholderText> <w:DoNotPromoteQF /> <w:LidThemeOther>EN-CA</w:LidThemeOther> <w:LidThemeAsian>X-NONE</w:LidThemeAsian> <w:LidThemeComplexScript>X-NONE</w:LidThemeComplexScript> <w:Compatibility> <w:BreakWrappedTables /> <w:SnapToGridInCell /> <w:WrapTextWithPunct /> <w:UseAsianBreakRules /> <w:DontGrowAutofit /> <w:SplitPgBreakAndParaMark /> <w:EnableOpenTypeKerning /> <w:DontFlipMirrorIndents /> <w:OverrideTableStyleHps /> </w:Compatibility> <m:mathPr> <m:mathFont m:val=\\"Cambria Math\\" /> <m:brkBin m:val=\\"before\\" /> <m:brkBinSub m:val=\\"&#45;-\\" /> <m:smallFrac m:val=\\"off\\" /> <m:dispDef /> <m:lMargin m:val=\\"0\\" /> <m:rMargin m:val=\\"0\\" /> <m:defJc m:val=\\"centerGroup\\" /> <m:wrapIndent m:val=\\"1440\\" /> <m:intLim m:val=\\"subSup\\" /> <m:naryLim m:val=\\"undOvr\\" /> </m:mathPr></w:WordDocument> </xml><![endif]--><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <w:LatentStyles DefLockedState=\\"false\\" DefUnhideWhenUsed=\\"true\\"   DefSemiHidden=\\"true\\" DefQFormat=\\"false\\" DefPriority=\\"99\\"   LatentStyleCount=\\"267\\"> <w:LsdException Locked=\\"false\\" Priority=\\"0\\" SemiHidden=\\"false\\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\\"false\\" QFormat=\\"true\\" Name=\\"Normal\\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\\"false\\" Priority=\\"9\\" SemiHidden=\\"false\\"    UnhideWhenUsed=\\"false\\" QFormat=\\"true\\" Name=\\"heading 1\\" /> <w:LsdException Locked=\\"false\\" Priority=\\"9\\" QFormat=\\"true\\" Name=\\"heading 2\\" 