(147, 1, '2011-02-25 13:46:53', '2011-02-25 13:46:53', '<strong>Question: </strong>When is the best time to detox?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> That is really an individual choice. As a general rule, I would suggest a detox anytime you feel “toxic” or are experiencing symptoms that may be related to exposure to toxins. For many, this can usually be after a holiday binge since that is when our healthy diet usually gets thrown out the window.\r\n\r\nFor otherwise healthy individuals looking to detox for prevention of adverse health conditions, there is a commonly held belief by practitioners of various forms of traditional medicine that the body naturally wants to detoxify in the fall (getting ready for winter “hibernation”) and spring (coming out of “hibernation”). Whether this is true or not, I would say detoxing twice a year is sufficient for most people.\r\n\r\nInno-Vite has created a line of easy-to-use products, each developed to target a specific route to detoxification, but also formulated so that all products can be used back-to-back for optimal elimination of stored toxins.\r\n\r\nWhile everyone is encouraged to follow specified dietary recommendations, the products will still provide benefit on their own, making it an easy program to follow, especially for\r\n\r\nthe “first-time detoxifier.”\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at\r\n\r\n<a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com">dr.Know@inno-vite.com</a>.', 'Expert Advice – When is the best time to detox?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '82-revision-8', '', '', '2011-02-25 13:46:53', '2011-02-25 13:46:53', '', 82, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/82-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(15, 1, '2011-01-27 16:28:14', '2011-01-27 16:28:14', 'Berries are a good source of many health-promoting compounds. With each new published study on these delectable fruits, the strength of evidence builds and reveals their health benefits, especially for the cardiovascular system. Several human intervention studies using cranberries, blueberries and strawberries (either fresh, as juice, freeze-dried or extracts) have demonstrated significant improvements in cholesterol levels, total plasma antioxidant capacity and glucose metabolism. These benefits were seen in both healthy individuals and in those with existing risk factors.\r\n\r\nHowever, the rise of berries to cardiovascular fame started long before these conventional medical studies. In fact, the cardiovascular benefits of berries can be traced right back to traditional medicine — more specifically botanical medicine.\r\n\r\nThe Doctrine of Signatures states that an herb or plant sometimes gives a clue about what it is good for through its appearance (like the ginseng root looking like a human body or a walnut looking like a brain). Following the same Doctrine of Signatures, strawberries are red and shaped like a heart so they are hood for the heart. In one study, it was found that strawberry consumers, in fact, have lower blood pressure than those who seldom ate strawberries.\r\n\r\nMost berries are reddish to purplish in colour — the colour of blood (red in the arteries, purple in the veins). The compounds that give berries their color are called anthocyanins. They strengthen the inner lining of the arteries, and recent research confirms that eating berries like blueberries, acai berries, cranberries, strawberries and cherries offers some definite cardiovascular benefits.\r\n\r\nIn fact, common problems with arteries, including angina (chest pain), congestive heart failure, intermittent claudication (pain, cramps, numbness or a sense of fatigue in the leg after even minimal exertion), peripheral arterial disease, strokes, and heart attacks, are all conditions for which the risk can be lowered through a diet high in berries.\r\n\r\nThe anthocyanins also work synergistically with vitamin C and other key nutrients to strengthen the capillary (tiny blood vessel) system by promoting the production of quality collagen — the building block of tissues. Anthocyanins also promote vasodilation (dilation blood vessels) and helps prevent platelets from clumping and forming blood clots.\r\n\r\nNot only have studies shown that anthocyanins can help prevent blood clots, improve blood circulation, relax blood vessels, and prevent arthrosclerosis, but scientists have also uncovered a whole host of other powerful effects, including antiviral and antiallergenic properties. Some research even suggests that anthocyanins can prevent cancer at a molecular level.\r\n\r\nA Harvard study found that those eating the most strawberries had the lowest blood levels of C-reactive protein (a marker for inflammation in the blood vessels), and lower cholesterol levels than those who consumed less.\r\n\r\nHerbalists have long known that hawthorn berry is one of the best herbs for heart health or cardiovascular health and modern research is just catching up now.\r\n\r\nAcerola cherries also contain anthocyanins like other berries, but they also contain many times more vitamin C than oranges. Acerola cherries can help with high blood pressure, protect against blood clotting and bruising, aid in collagen formation, and help to prevent arthrosclerosis.\r\n\r\nBlueberries offer protection to the brain against damage from ischemic stroke. Results of research at the University of Maine concluded that a diet of wild blueberries may reduce risk from cardiovascular disease, help regulate blood pressure, and combat atherosclerosis.\r\n\r\nSo, while an apple a day can still keep the doctor away, make sure you’re also getting a daily dose of berries as well.', 'Berrilicious!', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'berrilicious', '', '', '2011-01-27 21:09:10', '2011-01-27 21:09:10', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=15', 0, 'post', '', 0),
