(22, 1, '2011-01-27 16:32:14', '2011-01-27 16:32:14', 'Addiction to chocolate (AKA cocoa) predates most other addictions, and studies in recent years are suggesting this may be one addiction that’s healthy! Headlines and special news segments on the newly found cardiovascular benefits of chocolate have been popping up on a regular basis for years now.\r\n\r\nThis has aroused a deeper investigation into the many cardiovascular and cognitive benefits of chocolate, and led to the term “the chocolate paradox” — an indulgent fatty food that offers an assortment of health benefits. All this positive media coverage has transformed chocolate into a trendy functional food, and now, nutritional supplements.\r\n\r\nEven though chocolate is considered the most craved food in North America, unfortunately, guilt sets in after indulging. A 2009 review published in the journal <em>Circulation</em>, discussed the clinically relevant cardiovascular effects of cocoa, focusing on potential mechanisms and potential clinical implications associated with its consumption.\r\n\r\nHere are a few healthful reasons for keeping the chocolate addiction going:\r\n<h1>Cocoa Flavanols as Antioxidants</h1>\r\nAntioxidants are substances that may protect cells from the damage caused by unstable molecules known as free radicals. Antioxidants such as flavanols in chocolate can prevent LDL (bad cholesterol) from oxidizing and may reduce atherosclerosis (hardening of the arteries).\r\n<h1>Modulation of Vascular Function</h1>\r\nDiseases such as stress, ischemia (short oxygen supply), atherosclerosis, diabetes, and hypertension can impair the functioning of the inner layer of blood vessels (arterial endothelium), which has been shown to be a significant early event in the formation of arterial plaque (atherogenesis). The consumption of dark chocolate by healthy volunteers has been shown to dilate the arteries and increase their elasticity, thereby protecting the vascular system.\r\n<h1>Inhibition of Platelets</h1>\r\nThe clumping of platelets is the critical event that starts a blood clot, which can lead to a heart attack. Several studies have provided strong support for the ability of cocoa flavanols to prevent platelets from clumping. In fact, this effect may be just as potent as taking a daily dose of baby aspirin (but cocoa comes with a host of other health benefits and none of the side effects of aspirin).\r\n<h1>Antihypertensive Effects</h1>\r\nThe results of two separate studies in healthy subjects and later in hypertensive patients have shown possible benefits of cocoa in lowering blood pressure.\r\n<h1>Anti-inflammatory Effect.</h1>\r\nFlavanols from cocoa have also been shown to promote anti-inflammatory activities that protect cardiovascular health.\r\n\r\nFlavonoids are the part of cocoa that’s important for health benefits. While they can also be found in high concentrations in certain fruits and vegetables (such as certain teas, grape juice, wine, and various berries), cocoa has the highest content compared to these other sources.\r\n\r\nDoes this mean it''s a good idea to grab a chocolate-flavoured “candy bar” and scarf it down every day? NO! Not at all. It is important to distinguish cocoa from chocolate-flavoured candy. “Candy chocolate” is made when cocoa is combined with refined sugar, flavourings (most times artificial), and eventually milk and other ingredients into a solid food product. Even solid milk chocolate wouldn’t be considered “real” chocolate. Instead, consider adding small amounts of plain, all natural, dark chocolate to your daily diet.\r\n\r\nStudies have demonstrated quite convincingly that dark chocolate, particularly with a cocoa content of at least 70%, reduces oxidative stress and improves vascular and platelet function. So if you’re a chocoholic, don’t feel guilty… as long as you reach for the “good stuff.”', 'Dark Chocolate — an addiction that might be healthy!  ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'dark-chocolate-%e2%80%94-an-addiction-that-might-be-healthy', '', '', '2011-01-27 23:41:07', '2011-01-27 23:41:07', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=22', 0, 'post', '', 0),
