(63, 1, '2011-01-27 23:53:31', '2011-01-27 23:53:31', 'You are what you eat and eating the right food will keep your heart healthy.And keeping your heart healthy is core to optimum health.\r\n\r\nClearly certain foods can reduce the risk for heart disease.\r\n\r\nThe following top 10 heart friendly foods are important for the health of your heart:\r\n<h1>1. Salmon</h1>\r\nSalmon Fish is an excellent source of omega-3 fatty acids that protect your heart by reducing both inflammation and the risk of blood clots. Omega 3s also work to keep your cholesterol levels healthy.\r\n<h1>2. Olive Oil</h1>\r\nOlive oil reduces your risk of heart disease by lowering your LDL cholesterol levels. Choose olive oil for cooking (but do not heat), or make a nice dip for whole grain bread adding a bit of balsamic vinegar and a sprinkle of oregano.\r\n<h1>3. Oats</h1>\r\nOats contain beta-glucan, a soluble fibre that is responsible for cholesterol reduction. Eating about one-cup of cooked oatmeal a day significantly decreases blood cholesterol levels. Oats can be easily incorporated as part of your breakfast.\r\n<h1>4. Apples</h1>\r\nApples contain a compound called quercetin which acts as an anti-inflammatory and will help prevent blood clots as well. There are also many other beneficial compounds collectively called polyphenols in an apple, making this an extremely heart healthy snack. Research has shown that these polyphenols in apples could help reduce the risk of death from heart disease or stroke.\r\n<h1>5. Almonds</h1>\r\nAlmonds and other nuts contain healthy oils, vitamin E and other substances that will help keep cholesterol levels in check. Almonds are also a good source of protein and fibre. They make a great snack on their own, or you can sprinkle slivered almonds on green beans or asparagus with lemon juice as a deliciously healthy side dish.\r\n<h1>6. Red wine</h1>\r\nRed wine contains a powerful antioxidant called resveratrol. Resveratrol has been shown to be good for your heart by improving elasticity of blood vessels, thinning the blood, and improving glucose control. Be sure to enjoy red wine in moderation.\r\n<h1>7. Green leafy vegetables</h1>\r\nGreen leafy vegetables contain folate, which helps to keep homocysteine levels down. Green leafy vegetables have also been associated with better of memory retention as you age. Try using fresh spinach leaves or other greens for your favorite salad.\r\n<h1>8. Tomatoes</h1>\r\nTomatoes are packed with vitamins and lycopene, which has been shown to reduce heart disease risk. Make sandwiches and salads by adding thick slices of tomatoes, or enjoy tomato sauce on whole wheat pasta.\r\n<h1>9. Soy</h1>\r\nSoy as tofu makes an excellent protein substitute for red meat, which will reduce your saturated fat intake. Soy protein has been shown to help prevent heart attacks.\r\n<h1>10. Legumes and Beans</h1>\r\nBeans have been long recognized as among those "good-for-you" foods. They are nature''s second highest vegetable source of protein (the first is seaweed, if you happen to have a taste for it). Beans and their sister legumes, peas, make a nutritionally complete meal when combined with grains. Being high in soluble fibre–the same fibre found in oats–beans and peas can promote heart health. In addition,  it''s also important to remember that diet alone is not the answer. A healthy lifestyle includes regular physical activity, not smoking, controlling stress, along with a diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and adequate amounts of low-fat dairy, lean meats, fish and healthy fats.', 'You are what you eat and eating the right food will keep your heart healthy. And keeping your heart healthy is core to optimum health.  ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '39-revision-7', '', '', '2011-01-27 23:53:31', '2011-01-27 23:53:31', '', 39, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/39-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(69, 1, '2011-02-25 12:56:25', '2011-02-25 12:56:25', '<div><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="line-height: 24px;">Whether you went a little crazy over the holidays, or are simply trying to jump start a new diet regimen, there are specific foods that you can eat to help detoxify your system. You should aim for foods that are high in fiber and/or vitamin C as they’re great antioxidants for the body.\r\n\r\n5 Detox Foods to get You Started on the Right Path:\r\n\r\n</span></span></div>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Green leafy vegetables not only help with the detox, but they also help protect the liver.</li>\r\n	<li>Lemons and lemonade which are full of Vitamin C.</li>\r\n	<li>Green tea is full of healthy antioxidants and contains catechins which speed up liver activity.</li>\r\n	<li>Broccoli sprouts and cabbage. Both are high in fiber and help stimulate enzymes.</li>\r\n	<li>Fruit, fruit, and more fruit. Everything from strawberries to mangos — all full of vitamin C and are of course delicious and easy to add to any meal.</li>\r\n</ol>', '5 Detox Foods to get You Started on the Right Path:', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', '5-detox-foods-to-get-you-started-on-the-right-path', '', '', '2011-02-25 12:56:25', '2011-02-25 12:56:25', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=69', 0, 'post', '', 0),
