(81, 1, '2011-02-22 16:49:29', '2011-02-22 16:49:29', '<em>Makes 12 squares or 12 muffins</em>\n\n2 cups spelt flour\n1 cup white flour\n3 extra-ripe bananas, mashed\n1/2 cup canned pumpkin (or applesauce)\n1 tsp cinnamon\ndash cayenne\n2 Tbsp baking powder\n1 tsp vanilla extract\n2 tsp orange zest\n1 large orange, juiced (about 1/4 cup)\n2-3 Tbsp canola oil\n1/2 cup coconut milk (or preferred ''plant milk'' for lower fat)\n1/3 cup pumpkin seeds\n1 tsp salt (omit if using salted nuts/seeds)\n1/3 cup agave or maple syrup\n1/2 cup crushed pecans/nuts (optional)\n1/4 cup dried cranberries (optional)\n2 tbsp crushed/whole flax seeds (optional)\n\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\n\n*Preheat oven to 375-400 degrees*\n<ol>\n	<li>Add flour, dry spices, salt and baking powder to a large mixing bowl. Stir well.</li>\n	<li>Add in the soy or coconut milk, oil, vanilla extract, bananas, pumpkin or applesauce, orange juice and maple syrup. Stir well.</li>\n	<li>Fold in pumpkin seeds, 1 tsp of the orange zest, and additional nuts and/or dried fruit like cranberries. If you add in lots of dried extras, you may want to increase the liquid by a few Tbsp.</li>\n	<li>Lay a sheet of parchment paper over a shallow 8 x 14" baking pan/dish (for bars) or line muffin tin.</li>\n	<li>Pour batter into baking dish.</li>\n	<li>Over top the batter sprinkle pumpkin seeds, cinnamon, the other tsp of orange zest.</li>\n	<li>Bake for 15-20 minutes depending on how thick your bars/muffins are.</li>\n	<li>Remove. Cool. Serve!</li>\n</ol>\nBananas are rich in potassium and fiber. Nuts and seeds are rich in fiber, healthy fats, protein and vitamins. Pumpkins are rich in vitamin A and fiber.\n\nBON APPETITE!', 'Pumpkin Spice Orange Banana Bread (or muffins)', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '79-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-22 16:49:29', '2011-02-22 16:49:29', '', 79, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/79-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(82, 1, '2011-02-25 13:44:53', '2011-02-25 13:44:53', '<strong>Question: </strong>When is the best time to detox?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> That is really an individual choice. As a general rule, I would suggest a detox anytime you feel “toxic” or are experiencing symptoms that may be related to exposure to toxins. For many, this can usually be after a holiday binge since that is when our healthy diet usually gets thrown out the window.\r\n\r\nFor otherwise healthy individuals looking to detox for prevention of adverse health conditions, there is a commonly held belief by practitioners of various forms of traditional medicine that the body naturally wants to detoxify in the fall (getting ready for winter “hibernation”) and spring (coming out of “hibernation”). Whether this is true or not, I would say detoxing twice a year is sufficient for most people.\r\n\r\nInno-Vite has created a line of easy-to-use products, each developed to target a specific route to detoxification, but also formulated so that all products can be used back-to-back for optimal elimination of stored toxins.\r\n\r\nWhile everyone is encouraged to follow specified dietary recommendations, the products will still provide benefit on their own, making it an easy program to follow, especially for the “first-time detoxifier.”\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at\r\n\r\n<a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com">dr.Know@inno-vite.com</a>.', 'Expert Advice – When is the best time to detox?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'expert-advice-when-is-the-best-time-to-detox', '', '', '2011-03-01 14:40:03', '2011-03-01 14:40:03', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=82', 0, 'post', '', 0),
