(164, 1, '2011-04-26 15:40:07', '2011-04-26 15:40:07', 'The lovely and delicious pomegranate fruit is reminiscent of the lush gardens of Andalucia, Spain. The name comes from Pomme de Granada—apple of Granada. It was thought to have originated there. In ancient times, pomegranate fruit was regarded as a symbol of fertility due to the round shape, and abundant seeds. Recently however, science has discovered important compounds that indicate its benefits transcend ancient symbolism. Pomegranate is a delicious fruit (except for the hassle of peeling) with many beneficial compounds. Pomegranate has substances, such as polyphenols, that have antioxidant, anti-viral, and anti-tumour activity. It may also be helpful in maintaining healthy cholesterol and triglyceride levels.\r\n\r\n<strong>Pomegranate and Heart Health</strong>\r\n\r\nPomegranate has been shown to exhibit greater antioxidant properties than green tea, red wine and blueberry juice. As a scavenger of free radicals in the bloodstream, whole pomegranate polyphenols help regulate the degree of oxidation of proteins, lipoproteins, and vascular cells. Punicalagins and whole pomegranate polyphenols also assist in the regulation of several enzymes that control vessel dilation (via nitric oxide) and promote overall endothelial health. The end result is healthy blood flow and circulation, crucial keys in maintaining optimal cardiovascular health.', 'Pomegranate: A fruit from Heaven', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'pomegranate-a-fruit-from-heaven', '', '', '2011-04-26 15:55:59', '2011-04-26 15:55:59', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=164', 0, 'post', '', 0),
