(192, 1, '2011-04-26 15:38:24', '2011-04-26 15:38:24', 'The lovely and delicious pomegranate fruit is reminiscent of the lush gardens of Andalucia, Spain. The name comes from Pomme de Granada—apple of\n\nGranada. It was thought to have originated there. In\n\nancient times, pomegranate fruit was regarded as a\n\nsymbol of fertility due to the round shape, and\n\nabundant seeds. Recently however, science has\n\ndiscovered important compounds that indicate its\n\nbenefits transcend ancient symbolism.\n\nPomegranate is a delicious fruit (except for the hassle\n\nof peeling) with many beneficial compounds.\n\nPomegranate has substances, such as polyphenols, that\n\nhave antioxidant, anti-viral, and anti-tumour activity.\n\nIt may also be helpful in maintaining healthy\n\ncholesterol and triglyceride levels.\n\n<strong>Pomegranate and Heart Health</strong>\n\nPomegranate has been shown to exhibit greater\n\nantioxidant properties than green tea, red wine and\n\nblueberry juice. As a scavenger of free radicals in the\n\nbloodstream, whole pomegranate polyphenols help\n\nregulate the degree of oxidation of proteins,\n\nlipoproteins, and vascular cells. Punicalagins and\n\nwhole pomegranate polyphenols also assist in the\n\nregulation of several enzymes that control vessel\n\ndilation (via nitric oxide) and promote overall\n\nendothelial health. The end result is healthy blood flow\n\nand circulation, crucial keys in maintaining optimal\n\ncardiovascular health.\n\n<a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/Pomegranate.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-170" title="Pomegranate" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/Pomegranate.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="250" /></a>', 'Pomegranate: A fruit from Heaven', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '164-revision-4', '', '', '2011-04-26 15:38:24', '2011-04-26 15:38:24', '', 164, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/164-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(205, 1, '2011-04-26 15:53:54', '2011-04-26 15:53:54', 'Question: <span style="color: #444444; line-height: 24px; font-size: 16px;">I visited my local health food retailer to ask what I could take for high blood pressure and they gave me your Inno-Q-Nol product. However, the label says nothing with regards to blood pressure (other than a warning). Can you please tell me if this product is beneficial for high blood pressure and what dose I need to take?</span>\r\n\r\nDr. Know: <span style="color: #444444; line-height: 24px; font-size: 16px;">CoQ10, and therefore ubiquinol (the active form of CoQ10), has been studied as a medication for hypertension with some great results. In fact, the blood pressuring lowering effect is what prompted Health Canada to require all CoQ10 products to carry a warning suggesting consultation with a healthcare practitioner prior to use if taking blood pressure medications (due to the potential additive effects). I’ve had quite a number of people call me to tell me that they’ve been able to stay off medications, while others were able to reduce the dose of their medications. A couple others in particular reported they were able to get off their blood pressure medications altogether. The dose needed to get this effect would vary depending on the individual, but my suggestion would be to start with 100 mg daily (take Inno-Q-Nol with food for best absorption) and work your way up over the course of several weeks or months until you see an effect. Of course, my advice would be to visit a Naturopathic Doctor or another qualified healthcare practitioner so they can monitor your blood pressure and recommend the dose of Inno-Q-Nol that’s suitable for you.</span>\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at <a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com">dr.Know@inno-vite.com</a>.', 'High Blood Pressure and COQ10 ubiquinol  ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'high-blood-pressure-and-coq10-ubiquinol-2', '', '', '2011-04-26 17:50:52', '2011-04-26 17:50:52', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=205', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(197, 1, '2011-04-26 15:42:05', '2011-04-26 15:42:05', 'The lovely and delicious pomegranate fruit is reminiscent of the lush gardens of Andalucia, Spain. The name comes from Pomme de Granada—apple of Granada. It was thought to have originated there. In ancient times, pomegranate fruit was regarded as a symbol of fertility due to the round shape, and abundant seeds. Recently however, science has discovered important compounds that indicate its benefits transcend ancient symbolism. Pomegranate is a delicious fruit (except for the hassle of peeling) with many beneficial compounds. Pomegranate has substances, such as polyphenols, that have antioxidant, anti-viral, and anti-tumour activity. It may also be helpful in maintaining healthy cholesterol and triglyceride levels.\r\n\r\n<strong>Pomegranate and Heart Health</strong>\r\n\r\nPomegranate has been shown to exhibit greater antioxidant properties than green tea, red wine and blueberry juice. As a scavenger of free radicals in the bloodstream, whole pomegranate polyphenols help regulate the degree of oxidation of proteins, lipoproteins, and vascular cells. Punicalagins and whole pomegranate polyphenols also assist in the regulation of several enzymes that control vessel dilation (via nitric oxide) and promote overall endothelial health. The end result is healthy blood flow and circulation, crucial keys in maintaining optimal cardiovascular health.', 'Pomegranate: A fruit from Heaven', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '164-autosave', '', '', '2011-04-26 15:42:05', '2011-04-26 15:42:05', '', 164, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/164-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(198, 1, '2011-04-26 15:35:14', '2011-04-26 15:35:14', '<strong><a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/stretching.jpg"><img class="alignright" title="stretching" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/stretching.jpg" alt="" width="250" height="317" /></a>Your heart beats 100,000 times a day! That’s 36 million times a year! </strong><strong>Don’t you think it deserves more attention?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>“Cardiovascular disease (CVD) still remains the leading cause of death in Canada, accounting for 32% of all deaths each year.”*</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>(*Statistics Canada)</strong>\r\n\r\nLuckily, taking a preventative approach can help lower your risk and keep your heart strong and healthy for years to come. Research efforts in recent decades have identified many risk factors that can contribute to the development of cardiovascular disease. 8 in 10 Canadians have at least one risk factor for heart disease or stroke. You can''t control your family history of coronary heart disease, age, gender or ethnicity. However, since there are many other risk factors such as smoking, physical inactivity, unfavourable lipid cholesterol profile and hypertension that are considered to be largely modifiable, many deaths and disabilities due to cardiovascular disease can be prevented.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Be More Active and Exercise: </strong>Exercise offers so many health benefits. Something as simple as a walk for half an hour a day dramatically reduces the risk of heart disease. “A lifetime of regular exercise improves brain function, allows people to be active and independent in their later years, and adds years to life,” says Steven Blair, PhD, professor of exercise science at the University of South Carolina.\r\n\r\n<strong>2. Eat Healthy:</strong> Whether you''re cooking at home or eating out, making heart-healthy meal choices will help lower your risk of developing heart disease. A healthy eating plan may also boost your overall feeling of well-being, giving you more energy and vitality. Heart-healthy eating focuses on lowering your intake of fat, especially saturated and trans fats. It also includes limiting salt while upping your fibre intake and making sure you eat five to 10 servings of vegetables and fruit a day. A healthy eating plan includes healthy meals from the four food groups as outlined in Canada''s Food Guide: vegetables and fruit; grain products; milk and alternatives; meat and alternatives. When you''re grocery shopping, look for the Health Check symbol on food packaging, the Heart and Stroke Foundation''s food information program, based on Canada''s Food Guide, to assure that the product contributes to an overall healthy diet.\r\n\r\n<strong>3.</strong> <strong>Maintain a Healthy Weight: </strong>Maintaining a healthy weight is one of the best things you can do for your heart health. Studies show that losing weight, even just a few pounds if you’re overweight, will improve your health. One easy way to shed calories from your diet is to drink water instead of sugary beverages. If your weight is normal, work to keep it there by reining in calories and exercising frequently. If you''re having difficulty maintaining a healthy weight, you may need to speak to your healthcare provider.\r\n\r\n<strong>4. Live Smoke-free:</strong> Smoking and exposure to second-hand smoke have many negative health effects that increase your risk of developing heart disease and stroke. Smoking contributes to the build-up of plaque in your arteries, increases the risk of blood clots, reduces the oxygen in your blood, increases your blood pressure and makes your heart work harder. Once you become smoke-free and avoid exposure to second-hand smoke, you will immediately reduce your risk of heart attack and stroke. The sooner you become smoke-free, the sooner your body can start to recover and it doesn''t take long to see the effects.\r\n\r\n<strong>5. Manage Your Stress: </strong>People with high levels of stress or prolonged stress are more prone to higher blood cholesterol, increased blood pressure or to developing atherosclerosis (narrowing of the arteries). Many life events such as moving, leaving school, changing jobs, and experiencing losses can cause stress. Daily hassles, such as being stuck in traffic, deadlines or conflicts can also be stress-provoking. It''s important to identify your stressors so you can learn to deal with them effectively.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/stretching.jpg">\r\n</a>', '5 Easy ways to help lower your risk of heart disease and stroke', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '150-revision-5', '', '', '2011-04-26 15:35:14', '2011-04-26 15:35:14', '', 150, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/150-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(203, 1, '2011-04-26 15:43:25', '2011-04-26 15:43:25', '<strong>Preparation time</strong>: 1 hour 20 minutes\r\n\r\n<strong>Serves</strong>: 4 people\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n\r\n2 large eggplants (approximately 3 lbs.)\r\n\r\n1/3 cup Virgin Coconut oil\r\n\r\n4 cloves of garlic, minced\r\n\r\n4 tbsp fresh parsley, finely chopped\r\n\r\n¼ cup Parmesan cheese, grated\r\n\r\nPinch sea salt and fresh ground pepper\r\n\r\n2 medium yellow onions, sliced\r\n\r\n15 oz. fresh tomato, red ripe, chopped\r\n\r\n1 cup whole milk yoghurt\r\n\r\n2 tbsp fresh dill, finely chopped\r\n\r\n2 tbsp chives, shipped\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Directions:</strong>\r\n\r\nSlice eggplants into ¾ inch rounds. Lay in a colander and sprinkle with salt. Allow to rest for 30 minutes. Rinse lightly and pat dry. While the eggplant is resting, heat a heavy bottom pan over medium heat; add just enough coconut oil to lightly coat the bottom. Add onions and cook stirring occasionally. Remove the onions to a plate. Preheat oven to 400ºF. Add enough coconut oil in a baking pan and place the eggplant slices. Bake them for 30 minutes in the oven, turning until golden brown. Heat a little more coconut oil in a pan and sauté the garlic for a few minutes. Add the tomatoes and simmer on low heat for 15 minutes Season with salt and pepper. Reserving half the parsley, stir together the yoghurt, herbs and season to taste. Pour half of the tomato sauce on top of the baked eggplants followed by onions and tomato mixture again and finish off with the yoghurt sauce. Sprinkle the cheese on top and bake for another 20 minutes. Scatter remaining parsley on top when cooked.\r\n\r\nEggplant is high in fiber, potassium and B Vitamins. Many of the health benefits of eggplant come from its dark purple skin. Eggplant contains lots of antioxidants that help protect your cells from free radical damage, and also helps lower your risk for coronary heart disease.\r\n\r\n<strong>Bon Appétit</strong>', 'Recipe for a Healthy Heart - Baked Herbed Eggplant', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '160-revision-7', '', '', '2011-04-26 15:43:25', '2011-04-26 15:43:25', '', 160, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/160-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
