(227, 1, '2011-10-28 16:40:36', '2011-10-28 16:40:36', '<strong>Probiotics has been one of the hottest trends of good-to-eat foods in the recent years. However, if you are confused with terms like probiotics and prebiotics, you are not the only one!</strong>\r\n\r\nBasically probiotics are “good bacteria” that help maintain the natural balance of organisms (microflora) in the intestines. They help us combat infection, inhibit the growth of disease- producing micro-organisms, promote good digestion and boost immune function. They occur naturally in foods like yoghurt and fermented foods, added to foods, or available as supplements. The normal human digestive tract contains about 400 types of probiotic bacteria that reduce the growth of harmful bacteria and promote a healthy digestive system. The largest group of probiotic bacteria in the intestine are species that produce lactic acid, of which <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em>, found in yogurt, is the best known.\r\n\r\n<strong>Why the need for Probiotics supplementation?</strong>\r\n\r\nA polluted environment, processed foods, chlorinated water, and heavy use of antibiotics and other medications can destroy the friendly microflora in our bodies and allow the undesirable bacteria to multiply. The imbalance of good to bad bacteria makes the body susceptible to intestinal toxicity, bloating, constipation, poor absorption of nutrients, yeast infection and other diseases.\r\n\r\nProbiotics have been used as a form of treatment for a variety of gastrointestinal diseases including irritable bowel, lactose intolerance, traveler’s diarrhea, and antibiotic induced diarrhea.  While scientific understanding of probiotics and their potential for preventing and treating health conditions is moving ahead, here are some uses of probiotics for which there is some encouraging evidence from several studies.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Daily digestive support</li>\r\n	<li>Help treat diarrhea or constipation</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and treat infections of the urinary tract or female genital tract</li>\r\n	<li>Help treat irritable bowel syndrome</li>\r\n	<li>Help shorten how long an intestinal infection lasts that is caused by a bacterium called <em>Clostridium difficile</em></li>\r\n	<li>Help<strong> </strong>prevent  and treat “traveler’s diarrhea”</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and treat pouchitis (a condition that can follow surgery to remove the colon)</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and manage atopic dermatitis (eczema) in children</li>\r\n	<li>Help reduce recurrence of bladder cancer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSome experts believe probiotics to be more essential to human health than multivitamins – and there is much evidence to suggest that this could be true. Daily consumption of a well-studied strain(s) of probiotics is a simple and cost-effective way to protect your overall health from the ravages of the 21<sup>st</sup> century.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.probioticsincanada.com/">For more information click here to visit Probioticscanada.com</a>', 'What are Probiotics?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-are-probiotics', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=227', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(228, 1, '2011-10-28 16:15:31', '2011-10-28 16:15:31', '<strong>Probiotics has been one of the hottest trends of good-to-eat foods in the recent years. However, if you are confused with terms like probiotics and prebiotics, you are not the only one!</strong>\n\nBasically probiotics are “good bacteria” that help maintain the natural balance of organisms (microflora) in the intestines. They help us combat infection, inhibit the growth of disease- producing micro-organisms, promote good digestion and boost immune function. They occur naturally in foods like yoghurt and fermented foods, added to foods, or available as supplements. The normal human digestive tract contains about 400 types of probiotic bacteria that reduce the growth of harmful bacteria and promote a healthy digestive system. The largest group of probiotic bacteria in the intestine are species that produce lactic acid, of which <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em>, found in yogurt, is the best known.\n\n<strong>Why the need for Probiotics supplementation?</strong>\n\nA polluted environment, processed foods, chlorinated water, and heavy use of antibiotics and other medications can destroy the friendly microflora in our bodies and allow the undesirable bacteria to multiply. The imbalance of good to bad bacteria makes the body susceptible to intestinal toxicity, bloating, constipation, poor absorption of nutrients, yeast infection and other diseases.\n\nProbiotics have been used as a form of treatment for a variety of gastrointestinal diseases including irritable bowel, lactose intolerance, traveler’s diarrhea, and antibiotic induced diarrhea.  While scientific understanding of probiotics and their potential for preventing and treating health conditions is moving ahead, here are some uses of probiotics for which there is some encouraging evidence from several studies.\n<ul>\n	<li>Daily digestive support</li>\n	<li>Help treat diarrhea or constipation</li>\n	<li>Help prevent and treat infections of the urinary tract or female genital tract</li>\n	<li>Help treat irritable bowel syndrome</li>\n	<li>Help shorten how long an intestinal infection lasts that is caused by a bacterium called <em>Clostridium difficile</em></li>\n	<li>Help<strong> </strong>prevent  and treat “traveler’s diarrhea”</li>\n	<li>Help prevent and treat pouchitis (a condition that can follow surgery to remove the colon)</li>\n	<li>Help prevent and manage atopic dermatitis (eczema) in children</li>\n	<li>Help reduce recurrence of bladder cancer</li>\n</ul>\nSome experts believe probiotics to be more essential to human health than multivitamins – and there is much evidence to suggest that this could be true. Daily consumption of a well-studied strain(s) of probiotics is a simple and cost-effective way to protect your overall health from the ravages of the 21<sup>st</sup> century.', 'What are Probiotics?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '227-revision', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:15:31', '2011-10-28 16:15:31', '', 227, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/227-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(229, 1, '2011-10-28 16:43:31', '2011-10-28 16:43:31', 'You are probably wondering why eating nearly any commercial yogurt might not be as beneficial as a probiotic supplement. After all, traditional cultures have been consuming cultured, fermented foods like yogurt for years for digestive health promotion.\r\n\r\n<strong>The problem arises because...</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile traditional yogurts were phenomenal sources of beneficial bacteria due to their raw and unpasteurized state, most of today''s yogurts are pasteurized, unless specially purchased raw and unpasteurized from a local farmer. Sadly, pasteurization basically kills or sterilizes most of the beneficial and other bacteria during the heat processing; radically reducing most of the benefits.  Even most of the yogurts certified organic are pasteurized in some fashion.\r\n\r\nWith helpful bacteria less available in our food, it is crucial to consider supplementation with high-quality probiotics.', 'Probiotics vs. Yoghurt - If I eat yoghurt, should I still take probiotics?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'if-i-eat-yoghurt-should-i-still-take-probiotics', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=229', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(231, 1, '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '<strong>Consumers are more aware of probiotics than ever before, and yet it is now more confusing than ever when trying to choose which brand of probiotic is best for you.</strong> Here is a complete guide for you to help choose the right probiotics for you and your family.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>The Number of Strains vs. the Right Strain:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>The right strain is more important than the number of strains. A probiotic strain that is clinically proven to aid in a number of health conditions may be all that is needed. Often multi-strains are not tested in combination and one strain may inhibit another strain, thereby reducing the overall functionality of the probiotic. <em>A</em> <em>Lactobacillus</em> with broad spectrum benefits will work in the upper intestine, and <em>Bifidobacteria</em> will work in the lower intestinal tract, look for strains like <em>B. longum</em>, <em>B. bifidu and B. lactis.</em></li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Functionality:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>For probiotics to be effective they must provide the appropriate health benefits — this is <strong>specific to</strong> <strong>the condition, the dose and the strain</strong> <strong>of probiotic</strong>. For those looking for health maintenance — gut health and an immune system boost, a good, broad spectrum probiotic is optimum. For specific conditions, the dose may have to be increased to double or even triple the usual levels.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Safety:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>It is helpful to look for probiotics with a long history of use. Some probiotics have received a Natural Product Number (NPN), which informs consumers that the product has been reviewed by the Canadian Natural Health Products Directorate (NHPD) for quality and health claims. Look for the NPN number on the product label when selecting probiotics.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Origin :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Probiotics can come from human, animal, soil or plant origin. <strong>Human strains</strong> are most compatible with the human gut and can survive the stomach acid and bile salts.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Reliability</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Probiotics should meet or exceed their label guarantees of live cell count (CFU/g) at time of purchase and until expiration date. Probiotics are living microorganisms that live in little or no oxygen in the gut. They are sensitive to oxygen, moisture and heat. Production and packaging of probiotics should involve limiting exposure to oxygen by packaging in barrier packages and eliminating the oxygen by flushing with nitrogen. It is important to have low moisture in the probiotic capsule. Products should be protected from dramatic fluctuations in temperature.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Production of natural antibiotics</em></strong> : Some probiotics can produce other helpful substances like bacteriocins that reduce the numbers of harmful bacteria (one example is acidophilin produced by <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1). Certain strains can produce hydrogen peroxide that helps to reduce <em>Candida albicans</em>, which is responsible for yeast overgrowth.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Acid and Bile Resistance:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to survive the acid in the stomach and bile in the small intestine to reach the desired location in the gut (in some cases, fewer than 25% can make it through). Look for acid and bile resistant probiotics.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><em>8. </em></strong><strong><em>Colonizers vs. transients :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to colonize in the gut and they provide health benefits only on their way through the gut. Colonizers take up residence in the intestines, and then multiply and continue to provide benefits when they reach their destination. Colonizers can multiply 100 to 200-fold so 5 billion will soon become 500 billion or more. Some probiotics start with very large numbers of bacteria because often less than 25% even make it to the gut.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>9. </em></strong><strong><em>Production of enzymes:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Some probiotics are able to produce enzymes that aid in digestion — proteases, lipases, amylases, cellulase and lactase. Natural production of digestive enzymes declines with age in humans so look for probiotics that will help the microflora produce additional enzymes.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>10. </em></strong><strong><em>Individual Probiotic Needs</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Dairy-free, gluten-free, soy-free, corn-free, non-GMO, veggie capsules are all qualities important to some people. Make sure you read the label to find out if your probiotics meet your needs.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.probioticsincanada.com/">For more information click here to visit Probioticscanada.com</a>', 'How to choose the right probiotic? ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-choose-a-probiotic', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=231', 0, 'post', '', 0),
