(235, 1, '2011-10-28 16:41:52', '2011-10-28 16:41:52', '<strong>Question:</strong> I’ve been taking a 30 billion cfu/g probiotic and now I see there is a 70 billion cfu/g product. How much should I be taking and what is considered enough?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> That’s an excellent question and displays the confusion surrounding “potency” when it comes to probiotics. What you need to understand is that potency is strain specific. What this means is that each strain of a probiotic is effective at a specific potency.\r\n\r\nTo give you an example using E. coli, some strains (like <em>E. coli</em> O157:H7) can cause severe illness and even death if you consume extremely small amounts. Other strains of E. coli are harmless at much larger doses, and there are even strains of E. coli (like <em>E. coli</em> Nissel 1917) that are considered probiotics at a certain dose. This wide variation in activity within a bacterial species is exact why Health Canada requires all probiotic products to list strain identification. Just listing the species (like <em>E. coli</em> or <em>L. acidophilus</em>) is essentially meaningless.\r\n\r\nUsing Inno-Vite’s flagship probiotic (<em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1) product to clarify: Lactobacillus indicates the genus, acidophilus indicates the species, and lastly DDS-1 indicates the strain.\r\n\r\nTo group all probiotic species and strains together and list and overall potency is like grouping all minerals together and thinking one dose applies to all. To illustrate how wrong this is, take calcium, for example: 1000 mg of calcium is considered a good therapeutic dose. However, the same 1000 mg dose is toxic if you’re talking chromium (where a dose of 0.2 mg would be sufficient).\r\n\r\nSo yes, some probiotics may require 70 billion cfu to be effective, if that’s what the clinical trails determined. Others strains only require a dose of 100 <em>million</em> cfu. So when you’re choosing a probiotic product, don’t be fooled by the marketing game that’s being played out on the retail shelves. What’s most important is that you choose a product that has clinical research to show a particular strain actually exerts a “health benefit to the host” (the definition of a probiotic, which only clinical trials can reveal), and don’t be tricked by unscientific marketing.', 'Expert Advice Probiotics: How much do you actually need?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'probiotics-how-much-do-you-actually-need', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '2012-02-29 17:26:32', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=235', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(237, 1, '2011-10-28 16:44:18', '2011-10-28 16:44:18', '<strong>What is Candida ?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe <em>Candida albicans</em> yeast is one member of a community of hundreds of microorganisms that exist in delicate balance in the human intestinal tract. Under normal conditions only a small number of Candida organisms live in our intestines. A healthy colon contains about 85% friendly bacteria and 15% pathogens such as Candida. As a result of poor nutrition and modern lifestyles, many of us now may have the opposite ratio in our intestines: 15% supportive microorganisms and 85% harmful.\r\n\r\nCandida overpopulation (candidiasis) can contribute to a wide variety of health problems such as bloating, intestinal disturbances, diarrhea, fatigue, and vaginal discharge. However, the presence of one or many of these symptoms does not indicate a definite diagnosis of Candidiasis. As Candida is a normal inhabitant of the gastrointestinal tract, it is difficult to diagnose.\r\n\r\nMalnutrition, glandular imbalances, allergies, parasites and mercury, fluoride or lead toxicity are some of the other conditions that can mimic Candidiasis. In fact, Candida overgrowth often accompanies these problems, but may not be the cause. Therefore, before starting any anti-Candida program, get a thorough physical checkup to identify any other conditions that may require treatment as well. Generally, health practitioners use a questionnaire as a guide to the likelihood of Candida involvement. Patients with positive scores need to be put on an anti-Candida regimen. Please go to <a href="http://www.candidacanada.com/en/questionnaire.php">www.candidacanada.com</a><strong> </strong>to find out your score.\r\n\r\n<strong>What Causes Candidiasis?</strong>\r\n\r\nIn a healthy intestinal tract, populations of friendly intestinal bacteria like <em>L. acidophilus </em>keep Candida in check. Unfortunately, modern living is antagonistic to intestinal balance, including antibiotic, corticosteroids, oral contraceptive use, chemical pollution, nutritional deficiencies, chlorinated water, preservatives, high sugar intake, chronic constipation and stress. All these factors contribute to Candidiasis either by feeding the yeast, stressing the immune system, or killing the “friendly bacteria.” Poor diet can also instigate Candidiasis. Sugar, alcohol, and refined flour are “<em>Candida Super Foods</em>.”\r\n\r\n<strong>It’s Time to Listen to Your Body</strong>\r\n\r\nYou need not let Candida interfere with your health. To conquer intestinal yeast overgrowth, there are four things you must do:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Kill excess yeast in the colon and eliminate its breeding grounds.</li>\r\n	<li>Re-establish a healthy balance of intestinal flora.</li>\r\n	<li>Adopt a diet that starves Candida, but nourishes your body.</li>\r\n	<li>Strengthen your immune system, restoring its natural ability to fend off harmful organisms.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>The Anti-Candida Diet</strong>\r\n\r\nDiet plays a large role in the development of Candidiasis, so a modification in the diet is essential whether your condition is mild or severe. The dietary guidelines required for Candida recovery may appear challenging; however your determination and strong desire to get better should overcome these obstacles.\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="10">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width="50%" valign="top"><strong>The YES list</strong></td>\r\n<td width="50%" valign="top"><strong>The NO List</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Proteins</strong>\r\n\r\nBeans, deep sea fish, organic eggs, organic chicken or turkey, raw or soaked nuts and seeds, dairy-free cheeses\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sweetener</strong>\r\n\r\nStevia\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Vegetable</strong>\r\n\r\nGreen leafy vegetables, broccoli, cauliflower, cabbage, Brussels sprouts, bok choy, zucchini, onions, garlic, sea vegetables, all vegetables that are not overly sweet or starchy\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Grains</strong>\r\n\r\nHigh protein alternative grains, sprouted grains\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Condiments, Oils</strong>\r\n\r\nBraggs Amino Acids, flax oil, ghee, extra virgin olive oil, carob powder, tahini and other raw nut butters, vinegar-free pickles, vinegar-free sauerkraut, lemon</td>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Sweets</strong>\r\n\r\nBarley, corn, rice syrup, honey, sugar, maple syrup, milk products, pastries, cookies, candies\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Yeast and Fermented Foods</strong>\r\n\r\nAlcohol, miso, black tea, malted products, corned beef, yeast, cheese, soy sauce, vinegar, smoked meat and fish\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Common Allergenic Foods</strong>\r\n\r\nCorn, mushrooms, dairy foods, wheat\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Foods Easily Converted into Sugars</strong>\r\n\r\nDry fruit, refined grain pasta, sweet fruits (grapes, bananas, mangoes, etc.), fruit juice, white rice, refined flours</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<a href="http://www.candidacanada.com">For more information click here to visit www.candidacanada.com</a>', 'Suffering from Candida? Take action NOW  ', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'suffering-from-candida-take-action-now', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:31', '2012-02-29 17:26:31', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=237', 0, 'post', '', 0),
