(279, 1, '2011-10-28 16:43:31', '2011-10-28 16:43:31', 'You are probably wondering why eating nearly any commercial yogurt might not be as beneficial as a probiotic supplement. After all, traditional cultures have been consuming cultured, fermented foods like yogurt for years for digestive health promotion.\r\n\r\n<strong>The problem arises because...</strong>\r\n\r\nWhile traditional yogurts were phenomenal sources of beneficial bacteria due to their raw and unpasteurized state, most of today''s yogurts are pasteurized, unless specially purchased raw and unpasteurized from a local farmer. Sadly, pasteurization basically kills or sterilizes most of the beneficial and other bacteria during the heat processing; radically reducing most of the benefits.  Even most of the yogurts certified organic are pasteurized in some fashion.\r\n\r\nWith helpful bacteria less available in our food, it is crucial to consider supplementation with high-quality probiotics.', 'If I eat yoghurt, should I still take probiotics?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '229-revision-4', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:43:31', '2011-10-28 16:43:31', '', 229, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/229-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(280, 1, '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '<strong>Consumers are more aware of probiotics than ever before, and yet it is now more confusing than ever when trying to choose which brand of probiotic is best for you.</strong> Here is a complete guide for you to help choose the right probiotics for you and your family.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>The Number of Strains vs. the Right Strain:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>The right strain is more important than the number of strains. A probiotic strain that is clinically proven to aid in a number of health conditions may be all that is needed. Often multi-strains are not tested in combination and one strain may inhibit another strain, thereby reducing the overall functionality of the probiotic. <em>A</em> <em>Lactobacillus</em> with broad spectrum benefits will work in the upper intestine, and <em>Bifidobacteria</em> will work in the lower intestinal tract, look for strains like <em>B. longum</em>, <em>B. bifidu and B. lactis.</em></li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Functionality:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>For probiotics to be effective they must provide the appropriate health benefits — this is <strong>specific to</strong> <strong>the condition, the dose and the strain</strong> <strong>of probiotic</strong>. For those looking for health maintenance — gut health and an immune system boost, a good, broad spectrum probiotic is optimum. For specific conditions, the dose may have to be increased to double or even triple the usual levels.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Safety:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>It is helpful to look for probiotics with a long history of use. Some probiotics have received a Natural Product Number (NPN), which informs consumers that the product has been reviewed by the Canadian Natural Health Products Directorate (NHPD) for quality and health claims. Look for the NPN number on the product label when selecting probiotics.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Origin :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Probiotics can come from human, animal, soil or plant origin. <strong>Human strains</strong> are most compatible with the human gut and can survive the stomach acid and bile salts.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Reliability</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Probiotics should meet or exceed their label guarantees of live cell count (CFU/g) at time of purchase and until expiration date. Probiotics are living microorganisms that live in little or no oxygen in the gut. They are sensitive to oxygen, moisture and heat. Production and packaging of probiotics should involve limiting exposure to oxygen by packaging in barrier packages and eliminating the oxygen by flushing with nitrogen. It is important to have low moisture in the probiotic capsule. Products should be protected from dramatic fluctuations in temperature.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Production of natural antibiotics</em></strong> : Some probiotics can produce other helpful substances like bacteriocins that reduce the numbers of harmful bacteria (one example is acidophilin produced by <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1). Certain strains can produce hydrogen peroxide that helps to reduce <em>Candida albicans</em>, which is responsible for yeast overgrowth.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Acid and Bile Resistance:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to survive the acid in the stomach and bile in the small intestine to reach the desired location in the gut (in some cases, fewer than 25% can make it through). Look for acid and bile resistant probiotics.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><em>8. </em></strong><strong><em>Colonizers vs. transients :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to colonize in the gut and they provide health benefits only on their way through the gut. Colonizers take up residence in the intestines, and then multiply and continue to provide benefits when they reach their destination. Colonizers can multiply 100 to 200-fold so 5 billion will soon become 500 billion or more. Some probiotics start with very large numbers of bacteria because often less than 25% even make it to the gut.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>9. </em></strong><strong><em>Production of enzymes:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Some probiotics are able to produce enzymes that aid in digestion — proteases, lipases, amylases, cellulase and lactase. Natural production of digestive enzymes declines with age in humans so look for probiotics that will help the microflora produce additional enzymes.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>10. </em></strong><strong><em>Individual Probiotic Needs</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Dairy-free, gluten-free, soy-free, corn-free, non-GMO, veggie capsules are all qualities important to some people. Make sure you read the label to find out if your probiotics meet your needs.', 'How To Choose A Probiotic?  ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '231-revision-5', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '2011-10-28 16:41:31', '', 231, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/231-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(281, 1, '2011-10-28 16:43:43', '2011-10-28 16:43:43', 'DDS® is a friendly probiotic bacterium you’ve probably seen on the shelves at your local health food store and is best known as super strain of <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em>. While there are many different varieties of beneficial probiotic bacteria being sold today, DDS® is considered to be one of the most beneficial because of its <strong>long-standing scientific validation</strong> and <strong>proven ability to colonize </strong>in the human gastrointestinal tract.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Potent Formula:</strong> Each capsule contains 2.5 billion to 5 billion colony forming units of DDS-1 and other viable “colonizing” strains of human origin.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Superior Stability:</strong> Shelf stable, Live and viable for 2 years at room temperature. Freeze dried and nitro flushed packaging in glass bottles.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Superior Robust Strain:</strong> Survives stomach acid &amp; bile for a healthy intestinal flora.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Human Origin</strong> therefore adapts to the human body easily. Ensures lower intestinal activity.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Colonizing Strains (vs. transient strains):</strong> Attach to receptor sites on the intestinal lining and set up colonies resulting in the effectiveness of a much larger initial oral dose.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Superior Antibacterial Capacity:</strong> Produces Natural Antibiotics, Enzymes, Vitamins, Hydrogen Peroxide and Lactic Acid</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Backed by 40 Years of Clinical Research:</strong> Proprietary formulas with clinically proven results, patented and trademarked. Subject of over 200 studies worldwide.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Guaranteed Purity:</strong><strong> </strong>Non-Dairy, Hypo-Allergenic, No animal contaminants, Non-GMO, No artificial flavors, colours or preservatives, Gluten-free, Soy-free, Corn-free, Vegetarian.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Fortified with prebiotics</strong>, fructooligosaccharides (FOS)</li>\r\n	<li><strong>30 years of customer satisfaction</strong> around the world.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>All have NPNs. </strong>(Ultra Cran has EN)</li>\r\n	<li>Developed by Dr. S.K. Dash of UAS Labs, who has been the probiotic pioneer since 1979, served as Director of Food and Drug Administration for the state of South Dakota, Chairman of the National Probiotic Committee, currently Vice President of the International Probiotic Association and Scientific Advisor. Dr. Dash &amp; UAS Laboratories were the first to introduce Quality Control Standard for probiotics which is now used around the globe.</li>\r\n	<li>Available in Vegetarian Capsules, Chewable Tablets and Powder.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Why Inno-Vite’s DDS® Probiotics ?  ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '233-revision-5', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:43:43', '2011-10-28 16:43:43', '', 233, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/233-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(282, 1, '2011-10-28 16:43:01', '2011-10-28 16:43:01', '<strong>Question:</strong> I’ve been taking a 30 billion cfu/g probiotic and now I see there is a 70 billion cfu/g product. How much should I be taking and what is considered enough?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> That’s an excellent question and displays the confusion surrounding “potency” when it comes to probiotics. What you need to understand is that potency is strain specific. What this means is that each strain of a probiotic is effective at a specific potency.\r\n\r\nTo give you an example using E. coli, some strains (like <em>E. coli</em> O157:H7) can cause severe illness and even death if you consume extremely small amounts. Other strains of E. coli are harmless at much larger doses, and there are even strains of E. coli (like <em>E. coli</em> Nissel 1917) that are considered probiotics at a certain dose. This wide variation in activity within a bacterial species is exact why Health Canada requires all probiotic products to list strain identification. Just listing the species (like <em>E. coli</em> or <em>L. acidophilus</em>) is essentially meaningless.\r\n\r\nUsing Inno-Vite’s flagship probiotic (<em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1) product to clarify: Lactobacillus indicates the genus, acidophilus indicates the species, and lastly DDS-1 indicates the strain.\r\n\r\nTo group all probiotic species and strains together and list and overall potency is like grouping all minerals together and thinking one dose applies to all. To illustrate how wrong this is, take calcium, for example: 1000 mg of calcium is considered a good therapeutic dose. However, the same 1000 mg dose is toxic if you’re talking chromium (where a dose of 0.2 mg would be sufficient).\r\n\r\nSo yes, some probiotics may require 70 billion cfu to be effective, if that’s what the clinical trails determined. Others strains only require a dose of 100 <em>million</em> cfu. So when you’re choosing a probiotic product, don’t be fooled by the marketing game that’s being played out on the retail shelves. What’s most important is that you choose a product that has clinical research to show a particular strain actually exerts a “health benefit to the host” (the definition of a probiotic, which only clinical trials can reveal), and don’t be tricked by unscientific marketing.', 'Probiotics: How much do you actually need?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '235-revision-8', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:43:01', '2011-10-28 16:43:01', '', 235, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/235-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
