(375, 1, '2012-02-28 19:16:33', '2012-02-28 19:16:33', '<strong>Calcium supplements are commonly used to reduce the effects of osteoporosis; however, higher blood calcium levels from supplementation are believed to lead to hardening of the arteries, which can cause heart attacks and strokes. Therefore, it’s critical to consider other nutrients when taking calcium, especially nutrients that have a dual role in bone and cardiovascular health including vitamin K, vitamin D, B vitamins, zinc, silicon, etc.</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/running-in-field.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-365" title="running-in-field" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/running-in-field.jpg" alt="" width="280" height="236" /></a>Research published in the <em>British Medical Journal</em> suggests that regular use of calcium supplements will only marginally reduce the risk of fracture for osteoporosis sufferers. The study concludes that calcium supplements cause more cardiovascular events (such as heart attacks and stroke) than the number of fractures they prevent. When this study was published, the mass media reported this as “new,” when in fact, this is nothing new and has been known for quite some time. In addition, the researchers and media outlets interpreted this as: calcium is a killer! Of course they would. Fear sells.\r\n\r\nAs you might expect, there are concerns regarding the validity of the study itself (evidence suggests the researchers looked to prove a predetermined conclusion and ignored studies that didn’t report negative effects). Nevertheless, most in the clinical nutrition industry as well as many consumers acknowledge that bone is more than just calcium. In fact, the reason why many people do not receive a reduction in fracture risk from calcium supplementation is that, calcium alone can result in dense, but brittle bones.\r\n\r\nFocusing on the quality of bone, especially collagen production, and not just bone density, is what prudent healthcare practitioners and consumers should aim for. Collagen is the flexible scaffolding that gives bone a slight degree of “bend,” which is what reduces fractures (think of a dry, brittle tree branch that’s easily broken compared to a healthy and flexible branch). This is why good “bone health” products (as opposed to just calcium supplements) will contain nutrients for proper collagen production like vitamin C, silicon, zinc, lysine, and proline.\r\n\r\nGoing back to calcium increasing the hardening of the arteries, the researchers and mass media have it all wrong. Of course, the conclusion that “calcium is bad” makes sense if you’re using the conventional/modern medical paradigm to view human nutrition where all nutrients are considered in isolation, almost like drugs.\r\n\r\nFollowing a more traditional medical approach, nutrition is seen from a much more holistic viewpoint. In fact, most forms of traditional medicine around the world have acknowledged, not only the interconnectedness of the human body and various nutrients, but the interconnectedness of everything — and it’s time conventional/modern medicine caught up to this way of thinking.\r\n\r\nWhat the researchers should have recognized is that calcium is not necessarily the problem. In fact, it’s more of a vitamin K deficiency. The truth is that many people are vitamin K deficient according to recent studies on this essential nutrient. The critical point in this story is that vitamin K is needed to activate specific proteins that are intricately involved in calcium metabolism in the body.\r\n\r\nWithout enough vitamin K, your body will start to deposit calcium in the arteries (instead of in the bone). This is termed “arterial calcification,” which is now seen as the greatest predictor of a cardiovascular event — more so than high cholesterol, hypertension, family history, etc. Clearly, making sure you get sufficient amounts of vitamin K is one of the best things you can do to ensure both bone health and cardiovascular health.\r\n\r\nPeople should also consider other nutrients when taking calcium, especially nutrients that have a dual role in bone and cardiovascular health other than vitamin K. Things like vitamin D and magnesium are the first to come to mind, but there are many more like certain B vitamins.\r\n\r\nYou can start to see the complexity in using clinical nutrition for preventing or treating osteoporosis, and if we deviate too far from true nutrition and start to use high doses of single minerals like calcium in isolation, we’re in trouble.\r\n\r\n<strong>How to Make Calcium Work for Your Bones</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Balance your calcium intake. There are many calcium-rich vegetables such as beans and soy that do double-duty for the bones by alkalizing the system. Fish, seeds and nuts also offer additional choices. Consider supplementation with high quality calcium combination products.</li>\r\n	<li>Let the sun shine in! But do this in a healthy way. Some sunshine is required to allow your body to make adequate amounts of vitamin D3.</li>\r\n	<li>Supplement with vitamin D. For maintaining adequate levels of vitamin D, 1000–2000 IU per day is safe and adequate. If you think you could be vitamin D-deficient, ask your healthcare provider for vitamin D testing and then supplement accordingly.</li>\r\n	<li>Increase your intake of vitamin K. Most people get some, but not enough vitamin K from their diet. For optimum bone health, supplementation with vitamin K2 is recommended for nearly everyone. Exceptions include those using the blood-thinning drug Coumadin (warfarin), as this vitamin can interfere with the action of some blood-thinner drugs.</li>\r\n	<li>Dairy is an excellent addition to your bone health regimen — if tolerated — but don’t think of it as the sole centerpiece of your daily diet (see chart on page 2 for recommended daily intake for calcium).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong>Age or condition</strong></td>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong>Calcium Intake</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">&lt; 1 yr</td>\r\n<td valign="top">300–400 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">1–9 yrs</td>\r\n<td valign="top">500–700 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">10–18 yrs (especially during growth spurts)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1300 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">19–65 yrs (men) or menopause (women)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1000 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">&gt; 65 yrs (or post-menopause)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1300 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">Pregnant or breastfeeding women</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1200 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Calcium: Bone’s Friend or a Cardiovascular Foe?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '350-revision-3', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:16:33', '2012-02-28 19:16:33', '', 350, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/350-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(388, 1, '2012-02-28 19:28:42', '2012-02-28 19:28:42', '<strong>Postmenopausal osteoporosis</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is the type of osteoporosis that occurs in women after menopause as a result of estrogen loss. Bone is a living tissue that is always changing. After menopause, the decrease in estrogen triggers a rise in cells that break down bone tissue, creating a situation where bone loss occurs faster than bone formation. For many women, the result is decreased bone density and strength. This can lead to an increased risk of fractures, or bone breaks.\r\n\r\nNot all women get osteoporosis after menopause, but for those who have the disease, the effects of declining estrogen can be quick. Women can lose as much as 20% of their bone mass in the first 5 to 7 years after menopause. The good news: if you take the necessary precautions earlier in life, you can keep your bones strong and help protect yourself against postmenopausal osteoporosis.\r\n\r\n<strong>Quick Tips to prevent or manage postmenopausal osteoporosis:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Test Your Bones:</strong> Performed on a regular basis (frequency recommended by your doctor), repeated tests can show if your bone density has increased, decreased, or stayed the same. This is valuable information for you and for your doctor to determine if your current management plan is working well—or if you should consider another plan of action.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eat Smart:</strong> If you don’t supply enough calcium to meet the body’s needs, your body will take calcium from your bones. So adopt a healthy diet that will provide enough intake of calcium and all the other key bone-health ingredients, and also consider supplementing since food sources may not be sufficient for your needs.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Stay Active:</strong> Certain forms of exercise—weight-bearing exercise and muscle-strengthening exercise—build bone density and help slow bone loss. Other types of exercise, such as balance and posture exercises, can help decrease the risk of falls and broken bones. <em>National Osteoporosis Foundation</em> recommends 30 minutes of weight-bearing exercise on most days and strengthening exercises on each major muscle group 2 to 3 times a week. Before starting any exercise program, talk to your doctor.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Quick Tips to prevent or manage postmenopausal osteoporosis', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '354-revision-5', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:28:42', '2012-02-28 19:28:42', '', 354, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/354-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(376, 1, '2012-02-28 19:17:21', '2012-02-28 19:17:21', '<a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/image1.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-363" title="image1" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/image1.jpg" alt="" width="280" height="420" /></a>Millions of Canadians suffer from chronic musculoskeletal disorders such as arthritis and osteoporosis. These conditions cause pain — every day! The pain of these conditions can shut people off from everyday activities — a job, a sport, a walk. People with musculoskeletal conditions are also more likely to suffer from anxiety or depression. The prevalence of musculoskeletal conditions generally increases with age. Let’s take a look at some other conditions — besides osteoporosis — and possible ways to prevent them.\r\n\r\n<strong>Osteoarthritis</strong>\r\n\r\nOsteoarthritis is the most common form of arthritis. It affects one in every 10 people. It usually attacks the weight-bearing joints striking most often in the hips and knees, the largest weight-bearing joints in the body. It is responsible for 81% of hip replacements and 93% of knee replacements.\r\n\r\nOsteoarthritis, also known as “degenerative joint disease,” is caused by breakdown of cartilage, with eventual loss of the cartilage in the joints. Cartilage is a protein substance that serves as a “cushion” between the bones of a joint. When the cartilage degenerates, the exposed bones in the joint become inflamed and can be stimulated to produce new bone in the form of a local bony protrusion, called a “spur.”\r\n\r\nPrimary osteoarthritis is mostly related to aging. With aging, the water content of the cartilage increases, and the protein makeup of cartilage degenerates. Eventually, cartilage begins to degenerate by flaking or forming tiny crevasses. In advanced cases, there is a total loss of cartilage cushion between the bones of the joints. Repetitive use of the worn joints over the years can irritate and inflame the cartilage, causing joint pain and swelling. Loss of the cartilage cushion causes friction between the bones, leading to pain and limitation of joint mobility.\r\n\r\nA very common early sign of osteoarthritis is a knobby and bony deformity at the furthest joint of the fingers. These are referred to as <a href="http://www.medicinenet.com/script/main/art.asp?articlekey=6419">Heberden’s node</a>s. The bony deformity is a result of the bone spurs from the osteoarthritis in that joint. Another common bony knob (node) in many patients with osteoarthritis occurs at the middle joint of the fingers, and is called a Bouchard’s node.\r\n\r\n<strong>What Can You Do to Relieve the Symptoms?</strong>\r\n\r\nAlthough there is no cure for osteoarthritis, there are many ways in which you can relieve your symptoms and reduce the likelihood of things progressing. It is important that you learn about osteoarthritis and its treatments so you can take the lead in looking after yourself and your osteoarthritis. Here are a few tips to help you manage your osteoarthritis:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Reduce stress on the joints by:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Keeping your ideal weight. If you are overweight, losing even a few pounds will reduce the stress on your hips, knees and feet.</li>\r\n	<li>Pacing your activities through the day. Spread physically hard jobs (such as housework, mowing the lawn) at intervals through the day, rather than tackling them all at once.</li>\r\n	<li>Wearing shoes with thick soft soles that act as shock absorbers for your feet, knees, hips and back. For women it is also important to have flat heels. Raised heels alter the angle of the knee and hip and put additional strain on these joints.</li>\r\n	<li>Using a walking stick to reduce the weight and stress on a painful hip or knee.</li>\r\n	<li>Avoiding unnecessary activities that put a lot of strain on your joints. Think of modifying your home, car or workplace to minimise unnecessary stresses.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Exercise regularly. You need to keep your joints moving. There are two types of exercise that you need to do:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>First, strengthening exercises will improve the strength and tone of the muscles that act over your osteoarthritic joint. This helps to stabilise and protect osteoarthritic joints and reduces the pain.</li>\r\n	<li>Second, any exercise that increases your pulse rate and makes you breathless (aerobic exercise) can also reduce your pain and allow you to do more. Regular aerobic exercise encourages a better night’s sleep and is very good for your general health and well-being.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nRegularly undertaking both forms of exercise can greatly help people with osteoarthritis and over several months can relieve pain and improve movement.\r\n\r\n<strong>Injuries</strong>\r\n\r\nMost injuries are preventable. A few minutes of planning can make the difference between participating in your favourite activities and watching from the sidelines as you nurse an injury. No matter what the activity — walking, gardening, playing hockey, home maintenance — take some time to consider the risks and the steps you can take to eliminate or reduce those risks. Here are a few common-sense ideas for preventing injury:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Warm up before and cool down after strenuous activity — stretch your muscles and ligaments and loosen up stiff joints.</li>\r\n	<li>Make sure you have the equipment and skills needed to do a task safely.</li>\r\n	<li>Remove clutter that might cause you to trip or slip.</li>\r\n	<li>Use appropriate footwear for outdoor conditions — especially in winter.</li>\r\n	<li>Keep stairs and walkways clear and in good condition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Paget’s Disease of Bone </strong>\r\n\r\nThis condition causes your bones to grow larger and weaker than normal — bones may break rather easily. The disease can lead to other health problems, too, such as arthritis and hearing loss. Paget’s disease can present itself in any bone, but is most common in the spine, pelvis, skull and legs. The disease might affect one or several bones, but not your entire skeleton. More men than women have the disease, and it is most common in older people.\r\n\r\nNo one knows what causes Paget’s disease. In some cases, a virus might be responsible. It tends to run in families. You can treat Paget’s disease with medicine and sometimes surgery. A good diet and exercise as previously described might also help.\r\n\r\nMany people do not know they have Paget’s disease because their symptoms are mild. For others, symptoms can include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Pain</li>\r\n	<li>Enlarged bones</li>\r\n	<li>Broken bones</li>\r\n	<li>Damaged cartilage in joints</li>\r\n</ul>', 'Common Bone and Joint Problems', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '352-revision-3', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:17:21', '2012-02-28 19:17:21', '', 352, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/352-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(383, 1, '2012-02-28 19:18:25', '2012-02-28 19:18:25', '<strong><a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/soup.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-367" title="soup" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/soup.jpg" alt="" width="280" height="263" /></a>Servings:</strong> 4\r\n\r\n<strong>Preparation Time:</strong> 30 min\r\n<strong>Ingredients:</strong>\r\n1 medium onion, finely chopped\r\n2 cups homemade chicken stock or water\r\n1/2 cup rice, soaked overnight or at least a few hours\r\n2 cups plain yogurt\r\nSalt and pepper\r\n1 egg\r\n2 tablespoons butter\r\nJuice from half a lemon\r\n2 tablespoons dried mint, crushed\r\n\r\n<strong>Preparation</strong>\r\nSautée the onion in the butter until soft and golden. Add the stock and simmer until just below boiling point. Add the drained rice and cook until tender, add seasoning.\r\nBeat the egg lightly, add it to the yoghurt and blend together well, then add a little warm stock to the yoghurt and mix it. Pour yoghurt slowly into the stock, and stir over low heat for 10 to 15 minutes. Serve with few drops of lemon juice and garnish with mint.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nutritional information</strong> (per serving)\r\n<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">Calcium:</td>\r\n<td valign="top">100 mg</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">Vitamin D:</td>\r\n<td valign="top">20 IU</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Healthy Recipes - Yoghurt Soup', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '360-revision-4', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:18:25', '2012-02-28 19:18:25', '', 360, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/360-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
