(386, 1, '2012-02-28 19:47:53', '2012-02-28 19:47:53', '<strong>Question</strong>: I’ve been hearing how important vitamin K2 is for bone health. Is this something I can or should be giving to my children?\n\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> Yes, vitamin K2 is great for kids and, in fact, highly recommended for optimal bone development. Childhood is the best period to build bone mass and density, which will be drawn upon decades later. The rate of bone turnover and production in kids is much greater than adults, so on a per weight basis, children actually need more vitamin K2 than adults do.\n\nThis is the reason Inno-Vite’s Liquid K2 Drops lists dosing instructions directly on the label for children as young as one year old (this should be seen as the minimum dose, and it’s very safe to take more). This is the only K2 product in Canada that gives parents a convenient solution for children who cannot yet swallow pills, and it’s also easy to adjust the dose according to their age.\n\nA study published in 2009 looked at a dose of 45 mcg/day (of MK-7, a specific form of vitamin K2) and found significant bone-related benefits. The great news is that the exact raw material used in that clinical trial is the one that Inno-Vite has sourced, so it has proven safety and effectiveness in children.\n\nThis K2 raw material is also the only one in the market that also doesn’t contain things you’ll never see on the label, like dimethyl polysiloxane, which is an anti-foaming agent common in MK-7 ingredients. Just about every other brand uses the cheaper generics that look the same on a label, but are cheaper versions (both in quality and cost).\n\nYou’ll be happy to know that it hypoallergenic, contains essentially no soy proteins (so safe for most with soy allergies), and is non-GMO.\n\nIf you’re looking to use this as an oral alternative to the vitamin K injection given to newborns, you can email me for more information.\n\nHope this helps.', 'Vitamin K2 for Bone Health', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '356-autosave', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:47:53', '2012-02-28 19:47:53', '', 356, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/356-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(387, 1, '2012-02-28 19:19:41', '2012-02-28 19:19:41', '<strong>Calcium supplements are commonly used to reduce the effects of osteoporosis; however, higher blood calcium levels from supplementation are believed to lead to hardening of the arteries, which can cause heart attacks and strokes. Therefore, it’s critical to consider other nutrients when taking calcium, especially nutrients that have a dual role in bone and cardiovascular health including vitamin K, vitamin D, B vitamins, zinc, silicon, etc.</strong>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/running-in-field.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-365" title="running-in-field" src="http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/running-in-field.jpg" alt="" width="280" height="236" /></a>Research published in the <em>British Medical Journal</em> suggests that regular use of calcium supplements will only marginally reduce the risk of fracture for osteoporosis sufferers. The study concludes that calcium supplements cause more cardiovascular events (such as heart attacks and stroke) than the number of fractures they prevent. When this study was published, the mass media reported this as “new,” when in fact, this is nothing new and has been known for quite some time. In addition, the researchers and media outlets interpreted this as: calcium is a killer! Of course they would. Fear sells.\r\n\r\nAs you might expect, there are concerns regarding the validity of the study itself (evidence suggests the researchers looked to prove a predetermined conclusion and ignored studies that didn’t report negative effects). Nevertheless, most in the clinical nutrition industry as well as many consumers acknowledge that bone is more than just calcium. In fact, the reason why many people do not receive a reduction in fracture risk from calcium supplementation is that, calcium alone can result in dense, but brittle bones.\r\n\r\nFocusing on the quality of bone, especially collagen production, and not just bone density, is what prudent healthcare practitioners and consumers should aim for. Collagen is the flexible scaffolding that gives bone a slight degree of “bend,” which is what reduces fractures (think of a dry, brittle tree branch that’s easily broken compared to a healthy and flexible branch). This is why good “bone health” products (as opposed to just calcium supplements) will contain nutrients for proper collagen production like vitamin C, silicon, zinc, lysine, and proline.\r\n\r\nGoing back to calcium increasing the hardening of the arteries, the researchers and mass media have it all wrong. Of course, the conclusion that “calcium is bad” makes sense if you’re using the conventional/modern medical paradigm to view human nutrition where all nutrients are considered in isolation, almost like drugs.\r\n\r\nFollowing a more traditional medical approach, nutrition is seen from a much more holistic viewpoint. In fact, most forms of traditional medicine around the world have acknowledged, not only the interconnectedness of the human body and various nutrients, but the interconnectedness of everything — and it’s time conventional/modern medicine caught up to this way of thinking.\r\n\r\nWhat the researchers should have recognized is that calcium is not necessarily the problem. In fact, it’s more of a vitamin K deficiency. The truth is that many people are vitamin K deficient according to recent studies on this essential nutrient. The critical point in this story is that vitamin K is needed to activate specific proteins that are intricately involved in calcium metabolism in the body.\r\n\r\nWithout enough vitamin K, your body will start to deposit calcium in the arteries (instead of in the bone). This is termed “arterial calcification,” which is now seen as the greatest predictor of a cardiovascular event — more so than high cholesterol, hypertension, family history, etc. Clearly, making sure you get sufficient amounts of vitamin K is one of the best things you can do to ensure both bone health and cardiovascular health.\r\n\r\nPeople should also consider other nutrients when taking calcium, especially nutrients that have a dual role in bone and cardiovascular health other than vitamin K. Things like vitamin D and magnesium are the first to come to mind, but there are many more like certain B vitamins.\r\n\r\nYou can start to see the complexity in using clinical nutrition for preventing or treating osteoporosis, and if we deviate too far from true nutrition and start to use high doses of single minerals like calcium in isolation, we’re in trouble.\r\n\r\n<strong>How to Make Calcium Work for Your Bones</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Balance your calcium intake. There are many calcium-rich vegetables such as beans and soy that do double-duty for the bones by alkalizing the system. Fish, seeds and nuts also offer additional choices. Consider supplementation with high quality calcium combination products.</li>\r\n	<li>Let the sun shine in! But do this in a healthy way. Some sunshine is required to allow your body to make adequate amounts of vitamin D3.</li>\r\n	<li>Supplement with vitamin D. For maintaining adequate levels of vitamin D, 1000–2000 IU per day is safe and adequate. If you think you could be vitamin D-deficient, ask your healthcare provider for vitamin D testing and then supplement accordingly.</li>\r\n	<li>Increase your intake of vitamin K. Most people get some, but not enough vitamin K from their diet. For optimum bone health, supplementation with vitamin K2 is recommended for nearly everyone. Exceptions include those using the blood-thinning drug Coumadin (warfarin), as this vitamin can interfere with the action of some blood-thinner drugs.</li>\r\n	<li>Dairy is an excellent addition to your bone health regimen — if tolerated — but don’t think of it as the sole centerpiece of your daily diet (see chart on page 2 for recommended daily intake for calcium).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong>Age or condition</strong></td>\r\n<td valign="top"><strong>Calcium Intake</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">&lt; 1 yr</td>\r\n<td valign="top">300–400 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">1–9 yrs</td>\r\n<td valign="top">500–700 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">10–18 yrs (especially during growth spurts)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1300 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">19–65 yrs (men) or menopause (women)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1000 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">&gt; 65 yrs (or post-menopause)</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1300 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">Pregnant or breastfeeding women</td>\r\n<td valign="top">1200 mg/day</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Calcium: Bone’s Friend or a Cardiovascular Foe?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '350-revision-4', '', '', '2012-02-28 19:19:41', '2012-02-28 19:19:41', '', 350, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/350-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
