(405, 1, '2011-10-28 16:59:19', '2011-10-28 16:59:19', '<strong>Question:</strong> I’ve been taking a 30 billion cfu/g probiotic and now I see there is a 70 billion cfu/g product. How much should I be taking and what is considered enough?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> That’s an excellent question and displays the confusion surrounding “potency” when it comes to probiotics. What you need to understand is that potency is strain specific. What this means is that each strain of a probiotic is effective at a specific potency.\r\n\r\nTo give you an example using E. coli, some strains (like <em>E. coli</em> O157:H7) can cause severe illness and even death if you consume extremely small amounts. Other strains of E. coli are harmless at much larger doses, and there are even strains of E. coli (like <em>E. coli</em> Nissel 1917) that are considered probiotics at a certain dose. This wide variation in activity within a bacterial species is exact why Health Canada requires all probiotic products to list strain identification. Just listing the species (like <em>E. coli</em> or <em>L. acidophilus</em>) is essentially meaningless.\r\n\r\nUsing Inno-Vite’s flagship probiotic (<em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1) product to clarify: Lactobacillus indicates the genus, acidophilus indicates the species, and lastly DDS-1 indicates the strain.\r\n\r\nTo group all probiotic species and strains together and list and overall potency is like grouping all minerals together and thinking one dose applies to all. To illustrate how wrong this is, take calcium, for example: 1000 mg of calcium is considered a good therapeutic dose. However, the same 1000 mg dose is toxic if you’re talking chromium (where a dose of 0.2 mg would be sufficient).\r\n\r\nSo yes, some probiotics may require 70 billion cfu to be effective, if that’s what the clinical trails determined. Others strains only require a dose of 100 <em>million</em> cfu. So when you’re choosing a probiotic product, don’t be fooled by the marketing game that’s being played out on the retail shelves. What’s most important is that you choose a product that has clinical research to show a particular strain actually exerts a “health benefit to the host” (the definition of a probiotic, which only clinical trials can reveal), and don’t be tricked by unscientific marketing.', 'Expert Advice Probiotics: How much do you actually need?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '235-revision-9', '', '', '2011-10-28 16:59:19', '2011-10-28 16:59:19', '', 235, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/235-revision-9/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(406, 1, '2011-10-28 18:56:07', '2011-10-28 18:56:07', '<strong>Consumers are more aware of probiotics than ever before, and yet it is now more confusing than ever when trying to choose which brand of probiotic is best for you.</strong> Here is a complete guide for you to help choose the right probiotics for you and your family.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em> </em></strong><strong><em>The Number of Strains vs. the Right Strain:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>The right strain is more important than the number of strains. A probiotic strain that is clinically proven to aid in a number of health conditions may be all that is needed. Often multi-strains are not tested in combination and one strain may inhibit another strain, thereby reducing the overall functionality of the probiotic. <em>A</em> <em>Lactobacillus</em> with broad spectrum benefits will work in the upper intestine, and <em>Bifidobacteria</em> will work in the lower intestinal tract, look for strains like <em>B. longum</em>, <em>B. bifidu and B. lactis.</em></li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Functionality:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>For probiotics to be effective they must provide the appropriate health benefits — this is <strong>specific to</strong> <strong>the condition, the dose and the strain</strong> <strong>of probiotic</strong>. For those looking for health maintenance — gut health and an immune system boost, a good, broad spectrum probiotic is optimum. For specific conditions, the dose may have to be increased to double or even triple the usual levels.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Safety:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>It is helpful to look for probiotics with a long history of use. Some probiotics have received a Natural Product Number (NPN), which informs consumers that the product has been reviewed by the Canadian Natural Health Products Directorate (NHPD) for quality and health claims. Look for the NPN number on the product label when selecting probiotics.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Origin :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Probiotics can come from human, animal, soil or plant origin. <strong>Human strains</strong> are most compatible with the human gut and can survive the stomach acid and bile salts.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Reliability</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Probiotics should meet or exceed their label guarantees of live cell count (CFU/g) at time of purchase and until expiration date. Probiotics are living microorganisms that live in little or no oxygen in the gut. They are sensitive to oxygen, moisture and heat. Production and packaging of probiotics should involve limiting exposure to oxygen by packaging in barrier packages and eliminating the oxygen by flushing with nitrogen. It is important to have low moisture in the probiotic capsule. Products should be protected from dramatic fluctuations in temperature.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Production of natural antibiotics</em></strong> : Some probiotics can produce other helpful substances like bacteriocins that reduce the numbers of harmful bacteria (one example is acidophilin produced by <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em> DDS-1). Certain strains can produce hydrogen peroxide that helps to reduce <em>Candida albicans</em>, which is responsible for yeast overgrowth.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><em></em></strong><strong><em>Acid and Bile Resistance:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to survive the acid in the stomach and bile in the small intestine to reach the desired location in the gut (in some cases, fewer than 25% can make it through). Look for acid and bile resistant probiotics.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong><em>8. </em></strong><strong><em>Colonizers vs. transients :</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Many probiotics are not able to colonize in the gut and they provide health benefits only on their way through the gut. Colonizers take up residence in the intestines, and then multiply and continue to provide benefits when they reach their destination. Colonizers can multiply 100 to 200-fold so 5 billion will soon become 500 billion or more. Some probiotics start with very large numbers of bacteria because often less than 25% even make it to the gut.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>9. </em></strong><strong><em>Production of enzymes:</em></strong><strong><em> </em></strong>Some probiotics are able to produce enzymes that aid in digestion — proteases, lipases, amylases, cellulase and lactase. Natural production of digestive enzymes declines with age in humans so look for probiotics that will help the microflora produce additional enzymes.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>10. </em></strong><strong><em>Individual Probiotic Needs</em></strong><strong><em>: </em></strong>Dairy-free, gluten-free, soy-free, corn-free, non-GMO, veggie capsules are all qualities important to some people. Make sure you read the label to find out if your probiotics meet your needs.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.probioticsincanada.com/">For more information click here to visit Probioticscanada.com</a>', 'How to choose the right probiotic? ', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '231-revision-7', '', '', '2011-10-28 18:56:07', '2011-10-28 18:56:07', '', 231, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/231-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(407, 1, '2011-10-28 18:55:52', '2011-10-28 18:55:52', '<strong>Probiotics has been one of the hottest trends of good-to-eat foods in the recent years. However, if you are confused with terms like probiotics and prebiotics, you are not the only one!</strong>\r\n\r\nBasically probiotics are “good bacteria” that help maintain the natural balance of organisms (microflora) in the intestines. They help us combat infection, inhibit the growth of disease- producing micro-organisms, promote good digestion and boost immune function. They occur naturally in foods like yoghurt and fermented foods, added to foods, or available as supplements. The normal human digestive tract contains about 400 types of probiotic bacteria that reduce the growth of harmful bacteria and promote a healthy digestive system. The largest group of probiotic bacteria in the intestine are species that produce lactic acid, of which <em>Lactobacillus acidophilus</em>, found in yogurt, is the best known.\r\n\r\n<strong>Why the need for Probiotics supplementation?</strong>\r\n\r\nA polluted environment, processed foods, chlorinated water, and heavy use of antibiotics and other medications can destroy the friendly microflora in our bodies and allow the undesirable bacteria to multiply. The imbalance of good to bad bacteria makes the body susceptible to intestinal toxicity, bloating, constipation, poor absorption of nutrients, yeast infection and other diseases.\r\n\r\nProbiotics have been used as a form of treatment for a variety of gastrointestinal diseases including irritable bowel, lactose intolerance, traveler’s diarrhea, and antibiotic induced diarrhea.  While scientific understanding of probiotics and their potential for preventing and treating health conditions is moving ahead, here are some uses of probiotics for which there is some encouraging evidence from several studies.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Daily digestive support</li>\r\n	<li>Help treat diarrhea or constipation</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and treat infections of the urinary tract or female genital tract</li>\r\n	<li>Help treat irritable bowel syndrome</li>\r\n	<li>Help shorten how long an intestinal infection lasts that is caused by a bacterium called <em>Clostridium difficile</em></li>\r\n	<li>Help<strong> </strong>prevent  and treat “traveler’s diarrhea”</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and treat pouchitis (a condition that can follow surgery to remove the colon)</li>\r\n	<li>Help prevent and manage atopic dermatitis (eczema) in children</li>\r\n	<li>Help reduce recurrence of bladder cancer</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSome experts believe probiotics to be more essential to human health than multivitamins – and there is much evidence to suggest that this could be true. Daily consumption of a well-studied strain(s) of probiotics is a simple and cost-effective way to protect your overall health from the ravages of the 21<sup>st</sup> century.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.probioticsincanada.com/">For more information click here to visit Probioticscanada.com</a>', 'What are Probiotics?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '227-revision-5', '', '', '2011-10-28 18:55:52', '2011-10-28 18:55:52', '', 227, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/227-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(408, 1, '2012-02-29 17:26:29', '2012-02-29 17:26:29', '<strong>Question</strong>: I’ve been hearing how important vitamin K2 is for bone health. Is this something I can or should be giving to my children?\r\n\r\n<strong>Dr. Know:</strong> Yes, vitamin K2 is great for kids and, in fact, highly recommended for optimal bone development. Childhood is the best period to build bone mass and density, which will be drawn upon decades later. The rate of bone turnover and production in kids is much greater than adults, so on a per weight basis, children actually need more vitamin K2 than adults do.\r\n\r\nThis is the reason Inno-Vite’s Liquid K2 Drops lists dosing instructions directly on the label for children as young as one year old (this should be seen as the minimum dose, and it’s very safe to take more). This is the only K2 product in Canada that gives parents a convenient solution for children who cannot yet swallow pills, and it’s also easy to adjust the dose according to their age.\r\n\r\nA study published in 2009 looked at a dose of 45 mcg/day (of MK-7, a specific form of vitamin K2) and found significant bone-related benefits. The great news is that the exact raw material used in that clinical trial is the one that Inno-Vite has sourced, so it has proven safety and effectiveness in children.\r\n\r\nThis K2 raw material is also the only one in the market that also doesn’t contain things you’ll never see on the label, like dimethyl polysiloxane, which is an anti-foaming agent common in MK-7 ingredients. Just about every other brand uses the cheaper generics that look the same on a label, but are cheaper versions (both in quality and cost).\r\n\r\nYou’ll be happy to know that it hypoallergenic, contains essentially no soy proteins (so safe for most with soy allergies), and is non-GMO.\r\n\r\nIf you’re looking to use this as an oral alternative to the vitamin K injection given to newborns, you can email me for more information.\r\n\r\nHope this helps.', 'Vitamin K2 for Bone Health', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '356-revision-6', '', '', '2012-02-29 17:26:29', '2012-02-29 17:26:29', '', 356, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/356-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(413, 1, '2012-04-30 11:20:50', '2012-04-30 11:20:50', 'Over the last 3 or 4 years, the profile and popularity of CoQ10 ubiquinol has skyrocketed. The studies on ubiquinol are slowly reaching the industry and healthcare professionals and this incredible therapeutic product looks to continue its upward trajectory.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, this popularity can lead to the market being flooded with products.  Therefore, it is extremely important to review the intricacies of this ingredient and make an informed choice at the store.\r\n\r\nTo start, ubiquinol as a molecule is not new. It’s the active (reduced) form of coenzyme Q10, and it has been well known about for decades. However, due to its unstable nature, it only reached the market about 4-5 years ago after extensive research and development to stabilize the molecule.\r\n\r\nCurrently, there is only one manufacturer globally who is mass-producing ubiquinol for use in supplements—Kaneka. While Kaneka has done a great job creating a product stable enough to be used in supplements, due to its instability, it needs to be handled delicately. For this reason, it’s important that ubiquinol supplements are manufactured in oxygen-free equipment (nitrogen-flushed to eliminate oxidation during the manufacturing process). It’s also important that steps be taken to prevent oxidation of ubiquinol in the finished product (since oxygen will travel through the bottles and through the gelatin softgels or capsules).\r\n\r\nThis is important since ubiquinol can readily oxidize back to ubiquinone (standard CoQ10, which isn’t as effective for many people). Considering the increase in cost for ubiquinol, it’s important that a consumer paying extra to buy ubiquinol, actually gets ubiquinol (and not inexpensive ubiquinone).\r\n\r\nWhile most good manufacturers might have the ability to properly handle ubiquinol, Inno-Vite is the only Canadian company to license the patent that addresses oxidation of ubiquinol in a finished product. With this patent, Inno-Vite can guarantee that all products under the Inno-Q-Nol™ line are 100% ubiquinol at the expiry date. (including the water-soluble line, AquaSorb™, with its unprecedented absorption properties.)\r\nAlso Inno-Q-Nol is NON GMO!', 'Stabilizing Ubiquinol to Realize its Full Potential', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'stabilizing-ubiquinol-to-realize-its-full-potential', '', '', '2012-04-30 11:20:50', '2012-04-30 11:20:50', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=413', 0, 'post', '', 0),
