(452, 1, '2012-04-29 19:57:47', '2012-04-29 19:57:47', '<h2>A Recipe for a Healthy Heart</h2>\r\nServes: 4 people\r\n<h2>Ingredients:</h2>\r\n1 cup whole-wheat couscous\r\n1 cup vegetable stock or water\r\n½ cup  diced green pepper\r\n½ cup  cherry tomatoes, cut in halves\r\n½  cup canned black beans, drained and rinsed\r\n2 green onions, chopped\r\n1 tbsp finely chopped parsley\r\nJuice of 1 lemon\r\n1 tbsp olive oil\r\n1 tsp cumin\r\n1 tsp black pepper\r\n<h2>Directions:</h2>\r\nIn a small pot, bring the vegetable stock or water to a boil. Turn off the heat and add the couscous. Let it sit for 5 minutes and then fluff with a fork and transfer it to a large bowl.\r\nAdd the rest of the ingredients and toss.\r\nChill for 1 hour and serve cold.\r\n\r\nThis salad is a good source of whole grains and beans, and a healthy alternative to meat.', 'Cuuscous Salad', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '423-revision-5', '', '', '2012-04-29 19:57:47', '2012-04-29 19:57:47', '', 423, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/423-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(453, 1, '2012-04-29 20:09:38', '2012-04-29 20:09:38', '<h2>Question:</h2>\r\nNow that L-carnitine is available in Canada, should I take it for my heart if I’m already taking Inno-Q-Nol™?\r\n<h2>Dr. Know Answer:</h2>\r\nThat’s an excellent question, and I’ll start with the conclusion—yes. The reason why Inno-Q-Nol™ (CoQ10 ubiquinol) is so great for your heart is that it improves the efficiency of the energy-making process in our bodies. More specifically, ubiquinol improves the process of making energy that involves oxygen—called aerobic respiration or oxidative phosphorylation, and this is responsible for meeting up to 90% of our energy needs.\r\n\r\nL-carnitine’s role in energy metabolism is to transport long fatty acids into the mitochondria, where ubiquinol has its action. Fat is the preferred fuel for mitochondria since it’s so energy-dense, so L-carnitine is the perfect complement to CoQ10/ubiquinol.\r\n\r\nEven more, CoQ10/ubiquinol not only improves energy production when paired with L-carnitine, but may also theoretically help reduce the free-radicals produced during the energy-making process. Why? The process of producing energy requires electrons to be passed down a biological “wire” called the electron transport chain. If there is a shortage of CoQ10/ubiquinol (a break in the wire), it could result in electron leakage, which will go on to form free-radicals and, in turn, may eventually result in some negative consequences.\r\n\r\nSo while it’s great that L-carnitine is finally available in Canada, the best scenario would be to pair it with CoQ10/ubiquinol.', 'Expert Advice from Dr Know', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '422-revision-4', '', '', '2012-04-29 20:09:38', '2012-04-29 20:09:38', '', 422, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/422-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(454, 1, '2012-04-29 20:13:59', '2012-04-29 20:13:59', 'Coenzyme Q10 (CoQ10) is an extremely important nutrient that every cell in your body must have in order to produce energy. The heart has a huge demand for CoQ10; therefore, CoQ10 deficiency can trigger or worsen some serious cardiovascular problems such as angina, cardiomyopathy and high blood pressure.\r\n\r\nOne of the most remarkable studies on CoQ10 involved the significant improvement of individuals expected to die of heart failure. When these patients were supplemented with CoQ10, this miracle nutrient astounded physicians by improving blood pumping capabilities and reducing heart size, surpassing researcher’s expectations. Since this study many more clinical trials have been conducted to unveil CoQ10’s immense value in treating heart patients. CoQ10 has also been shown to be effective in reducing mild to moderate hypertension, as well as counteracting the serious adverse effects of cholesterol-lowering medications called statins.\r\n<h2>Ubiquinone vs. Ubiquinol</h2>\r\nUbiquinone is the standard form of COQ10. In order to generate cellular energy your body must convert ubiquinone to ubiquinol. As we age, our ability to convert CoQ10 becomes very poor; hence the best way to achieve optimal benefits of CoQ10 is the ready-to-use activated form – Ubiquinol, the biologically superior form of CoQ10.\r\n\r\nCompared to standard CoQ10 supplements, ubiquinol is absorbed in the bloodstream up to 8 times better; it reduced exercise-induced fatigue by 90% more and slowed aging 40% better. In experimental studies ubiquinol also shown to achieve 3.75 times higher plasma concentrations after 8 hours than standard CoQ10.\r\n\r\nIn a peer-reviewed, published human study conducted by cardiologists in Texas (published in BioFactors in 2008), they took Class IV congestive heart failure patients who had worsening health. These patients were essentially living on borrowed time and were switched to ubiquinol as an “experiment” (all other factors were kept constant).\r\n\r\nThe improvement in these patients’ condition was so dramatic when switched to ubiquinol, the lead researcher states, “We have observed improvement in CoQ10 absorption and have attained high plasma CoQ10 levels, rarely observed with any prior ubiquinone formulation.”\r\n\r\nAnother study published earlier this year demonstrated that just 150 mg/day of ubiquinol lowered cholesterol levels by 12.7% in just 2 weeks.\r\n<h2>Who should consider taking Ubiquinol?</h2>\r\nSupplementing with ubiquinol rather than standard CoQ10 (ubiquinone) is especially important for individials who may have difficulty with the natural conversion of CoQ10 to ubiquinol such as:\r\n\r\n- Middle-aged to elderly\r\n- Individuals suffering from specific conditions especially related to oxidative stress including diabetics, those with liver disease and with heart disease.\r\n<h2>How much ubiquinol should you take?</h2>\r\nThe recommended dose of ubiquinol varies based on each individual’s needs and the specific condition treated. However, those who are older may want to start supplementing with 200-300 mg of ubiquinol per day. 100-200 mg per day is a good maintenance dose for others.\r\n\r\nIMPORTANT NOTE: Not all CoQ10 ubiquinol supplements on the market are stable. Look for supplements produced using patented processes to guarantee stability. Make sure what you are buying is what you think you are getting.', 'CoQ10 ubiquinone or ubiquinol?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '415-revision-7', '', '', '2012-04-29 20:13:59', '2012-04-29 20:13:59', '', 415, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/415-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(455, 1, '2012-04-29 20:04:54', '2012-04-29 20:04:54', 'Carnitine is an aminoacid that helps the body turn fat into energy. Your body makes it in the liver and kidneys and stores it in the skeletal muscles, heart and brain. Carnitine has been proposed as a treatment for many conditions because it acts as an antioxidant. Antioxidants fight harmful particles in the body known as free radicals, which damage cells and tamper with DNA. Antioxidants can neutralize free radicals and may reduce or help prevent some of the damage they cause.\r\n<h1>Heart Conditions</h1>\r\n<h2>Angina</h2>\r\nSome good evidence shows that carnitine can be used along with conventional treatment for stable angina. Several clinical trials show that L-carnitine can help reduce symptoms of angina and improve the ability of people with angina to exercise without chest pain.\r\n<h2>Heart attack</h2>\r\nA number of studies have found that carnitine may help when used with conventional medicines after a heart attack. They suggested that people who take L-carnitine supplements soon after a heart attack may be less likely to have another heart attack, die of heart disease, have chest pain and abnormal heart rhythms, or develop heart failure.\r\n<h2>Heart failure</h2>\r\nSome studies have suggested that carnitine can help reduce symptoms of heart failure and improve exercise capacity in people with heart failure.\r\n<h2>Peripheral Vascular Disease</h2>\r\nDecreased blood flow to the legs from atherosclerosis or hardening of the arteries -- where plaque builds up in the arteries -- often causes an aching or cramping pain in the legs while walking or exercising. This pain is called intermittent claudication, and the reduced blood flow to the legs is called peripheral vascular disease (PVD). Several studies show that carnitine can help reduce symptoms and increase the distance that people with intermittent claudication can walk.\r\n<h2>Diabetic Neuropathy</h2>\r\nDiabetic neuropathy happens when high blood sugar levels damage nerves in the body, especially the arms, legs, and feet, causing pain and numbness. Some small preliminary studies suggest L-carnitine may help reduce pain and increase feeling in affected nerves. It is also possible that carnitine can help nerves regenerate.', 'What is Carnitine ?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '417-revision-4', '', '', '2012-04-29 20:04:54', '2012-04-29 20:04:54', '', 417, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/417-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(456, 1, '2012-04-29 20:15:49', '2012-04-29 20:15:49', 'Over the last 3 or 4 years, the profile and popularity of CoQ10 ubiquinol has skyrocketed. The studies on ubiquinol are slowly reaching the industry and healthcare professionals and this incredible therapeutic product looks to continue its upward trajectory.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, this popularity can lead to the market being flooded with products.  Therefore, it is extremely important to review the intricacies of this ingredient and make an informed choice at the store.\r\n\r\nTo start, ubiquinol as a molecule is not new. It’s the active (reduced) form of coenzyme Q10, and it has been well known about for decades. However, due to its unstable nature, it only reached the market about 4-5 years ago after extensive research and development to stabilize the molecule.\r\n\r\nCurrently, there is only one manufacturer globally who is mass-producing ubiquinol for use in supplements—Kaneka. While Kaneka has done a great job creating a product stable enough to be used in supplements, due to its instability, it needs to be handled delicately. For this reason, it’s important that ubiquinol supplements are manufactured in oxygen-free equipment (nitrogen-flushed to eliminate oxidation during the manufacturing process). It’s also important that steps be taken to prevent oxidation of ubiquinol in the finished product (since oxygen will travel through the bottles and through the gelatin softgels or capsules).\r\n\r\nThis is important since ubiquinol can readily oxidize back to ubiquinone (standard CoQ10, which isn’t as effective for many people). Considering the increase in cost for ubiquinol, it’s important that a consumer paying extra to buy ubiquinol, actually gets ubiquinol (and not inexpensive ubiquinone).\r\n\r\nWhile most good manufacturers might have the ability to properly handle ubiquinol, Inno-Vite is the only Canadian company to license the patent that addresses oxidation of ubiquinol in a finished product. With this patent, Inno-Vite can guarantee that all products under the Inno-Q-Nol™ line are 100% ubiquinol at the expiry date. (including the water-soluble line, AquaSorb™, with its unprecedented absorption properties.)\r\nAlso Inno-Q-Nol is NON GMO!', 'Stabilizing Ubiquinol to Realize its Full Potential', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '413-revision-4', '', '', '2012-04-29 20:15:49', '2012-04-29 20:15:49', '', 413, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/413-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
