(531, 1, '2012-10-31 14:26:58', '2012-10-31 14:26:58', 'Recipe for a Healthy Digestion\r\n\r\nPreparation time: 60 minutes\r\nServes: 6 people\r\nIngredients:\r\n• 1 large onion, diced\r\n• 3 stalks celery, diced.\r\n• 2 medium carrots, diced\r\n• 1 large leek, diced\r\n• 2 cups of pumpkin, cooked\r\n• 6 cups of vegetable broth\r\n• 1/2 tsp cumin powder\r\n• 1/2 tsp of cinnamon\r\n• Pinch of clove\r\n• Pinch of nutmeg\r\n• Salt\r\n1 cup of almond milk, rice milk or half and half\r\n\r\nDirections:\r\nAdd the first 11 ingredients into a stock pot over medium-high heat. Bring to boil and reduce to simmer. Simmer for 30 minutes and remove from heat. Allow to cool for 15 minutes. Puree soup in blender and return to pot. Finish with milk and season to taste.\r\n\r\nBon Appétit!', 'Harvest Pumpkin Soup', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'harvest-pumpkin-soup', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:48:40', '2012-10-31 14:48:40', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=531', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(532, 1, '2012-10-31 14:26:46', '2012-10-31 14:26:46', 'Recipe for a Healthy Digestion\n\n\nPreparation time: 60 minutes\nServes: 6 people\nIngredients:\n• 1 large onion, diced\n• 3 stalks celery, diced.\n• 2 medium carrots, diced\n• 1 large leek, diced\n• 2 cups of pumpkin, cooked\n• 6 cups of vegetable broth\n• 1/2 tsp cumin powder\n• 1/2 tsp of cinnamon\n• Pinch of clove\n• Pinch of nutmeg\n• Salt\n1 cup of almond milk, rice milk or half and half\n\nDirections:\nAdd the first 11 ingredients into a stock pot over medium-high heat. Bring to boil and reduce to simmer. Simmer for 30 minutes and remove from heat. Allow to cool for 15 minutes. Puree soup in blender and return to pot. Finish with milk and season to taste.\n\nBon Appétit!', 'Harvest Pumpkin Soup', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '531-revision', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:26:46', '2012-10-31 14:26:46', '', 531, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/531-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(533, 1, '2012-10-31 14:28:25', '2012-10-31 14:28:25', 'Consumers are more aware of probiotics than ever before, and yet it is now more confusing than ever when trying to choose which brand of probiotic is best for you. Here is a complete guide to help choose the right probiotics for you and your family.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Number of Strains vs. the Right Strain: </strong>\r\nThe right strain is more important than the number of strains. A probiotic strain that is clinically proven to aid in a number of health conditions may be all that is needed. Often multi-strains are not tested in combination and one strain may inhibit another strain, thereby reducing the overall functionality of the probiotic. A Lactobacillus with broad spectrum benefits will work in the upper intestine, and Bifidobacteria will work in the lower intestinal tract. Look for strains like B. longum, B. bifidum and B. lactis.\r\n\r\n<strong>Functionality: </strong>\r\nFor probiotics to be effective they must provide the appropriate health benefits — this is specific to the condition, the dose and the strain of probiotic. For those looking for health maintenance — gut health and an immune system boost, a good, broad spectrum probiotic is optimum. For specific conditions, the dose may have to be increased to double or even triple the usual levels.\r\n\r\n<strong>Safety: </strong>\r\nIt is helpful to look for probiotics with a long history of use. Some probiotics have received a Natural Product Number (NPN), which informs consumers that the product has been reviewed by the Canadian Natural Health Products Directorate (NHPD) for quality and health claims. Look for the NPN number on the product label when selecting probiotics.\r\n\r\n<strong>Origin: </strong>\r\nProbiotics can come from human, animal, soil or plant origin. Human strains are most compatible with the human gut and can survive the stomach acid and bile salts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Reliability: </strong>\r\nProbiotics should meet or exceed their label guarantees of live cell count (CFU/g) at time of purchase and until expiration date. Probiotics are living microorganisms that live in little or no oxygen in the gut. They are sensitive to oxygen, moisture and heat. Production and packaging of probiotics should involve limiting exposure to oxygen by packaging in barrier packages and eliminating the oxygen by flushing with nitrogen. It is important to have low moisture in the probiotic capsule. Products should be protected from dramatic fluctuations in temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>Production of natural antibiotics: </strong>\r\nSome probiotics can produce other helpful substances like bacteriocins that reduce the numbers of harmful bacteria (one example is acidophilin produced by Lactobacillus acidophilus DDS-1). Certain strains can produce hydrogen peroxide that helps to reduce Candida albicans, which is responsible for yeast overgrowth.\r\n\r\n<strong>Acid and Bile Resistance: </strong>\r\nMany probiotics are not able to survive the acid in the stomach and bile in the small intestine to reach the desired location in the gut (in some cases, fewer than 25% can make it through). Look for acid and bile resistant probiotics.\r\n\r\n<strong>Colonizers vs. transients: </strong>\r\nMany probiotics are not able to colonize in the gut and they provide health benefits only on their way through the gut. Colonizers take up residence in the intestines, and then multiply and continue to provide benefits when they reach their destination. Colonizers can multiply 100 to 200-fold so 5 billion will soon become 500 billion or more. Some products start with very large numbers of bacteria because often less than 25% even make it to the gut.\r\n\r\n<strong>Production of enzymes: </strong>\r\nSome probiotics are able to produce enzymes that aid in digestion — proteases, lipases, amylases, cellulase and lactase. Natural production of digestive enzymes declines with age in humans so look for probiotics that will produce additional enzymes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Individual Probiotic Needs:</strong>\r\nDairy-free, gluten-free, soy-free, corn-free, non- GMO, veggie capsules are all qualities important to some people. Make sure you read the label to find out if your probiotics meet your needs.', 'How To Choose A Probiotic?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-choose-a-probiotic-2', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:58:25', '2012-10-31 14:58:25', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=533', 0, 'post', '', 0),
