(539, 1, '2012-10-31 14:23:38', '2012-10-31 14:23:38', 'Question: I’ve been taking a 30 billion cfu/g probiotic and now I see there is a 70 billion cfu/g product. How much should I be taking and what is considered enough?\r\n\r\nDr. Know: That’s an excellent question and displays the confusion surrounding “potency” when it comes to probiotics. What you need to understand is that potency is strain specific. What this means is that each strain of a probiotic is effective at a specific potency.\r\n\r\nTo give you an example using E. coli, some strains (like E. coli O157:H7) can cause severe illness and even death if you consume extremely small amounts. Other strains of E. coli are harmless at much larger doses, and there are even strains of E. coli (like E. coli Nissel 1917) that are considered probiotics at a certain dose. This wide variation in activity within a bacterial species is exact why Health Canada requires all probiotic products to list strain identification. Just listing the species (like E. coli or L. acidophilus) is essentially meaningless.\r\n\r\nUsing Inno-Vite’s flagship probiotic (Lactobacillus acidophilus DDS-1) product to clarify: Lactobacillus indicates the genus, acidophilus indicates the species, and lastly DDS-1 indicates the strain.\r\n\r\nTo group all probiotic species and strains together and list and overall potency is like grouping all minerals together and thinking one dose applies to all. To illustrate how wrong this is, take calcium, for example: 1000 mg of calcium is considered a good therapeutic dose. However, the same 1000 mg dose is toxic if you’re talking chromium (where a dose of 0.2 mg would be sufficient).\r\n\r\nSo yes, some probiotics may require 70 billion cfu to be effective, if that’s what the clinical trails determined. Others strains only require a dose of 100 million cfu. So when you’re choosing a probiotic product, don’t be fooled by the marketing game that’s being played out on the retail shelves. What’s most important is that you choose a product that has clinical research to show a particular strain actually exerts a “health benefit to the host” (the definition of a probiotic, which only clinical trials can reveal), and don’t be tricked by unscientific marketing.\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at <a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com">dr.Know@inno-vite.com</a>.', 'Probiotics: How much do you actually need?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '527-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:23:38', '2012-10-31 14:23:38', '', 527, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/527-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(540, 1, '2012-10-31 14:28:25', '2012-10-31 14:28:25', 'Consumers are more aware of probiotics than ever before, and yet it is now more confusing than ever when trying to choose which brand of probiotic is best for you. Here is a complete guide to help choose the right probiotics for you and your family.\r\n\r\n<strong>The Number of Strains vs. the Right Strain: </strong>\r\nThe right strain is more important than the number of strains. A probiotic strain that is clinically proven to aid in a number of health conditions may be all that is needed. Often multi-strains are not tested in combination and one strain may inhibit another strain, thereby reducing the overall functionality of the probiotic. A Lactobacillus with broad spectrum benefits will work in the upper intestine, and Bifidobacteria will work in the lower intestinal tract. Look for strains like B. longum, B. bifidum and B. lactis.\r\n\r\n<strong>Functionality: </strong>\r\nFor probiotics to be effective they must provide the appropriate health benefits — this is specific to the condition, the dose and the strain of probiotic. For those looking for health maintenance — gut health and an immune system boost, a good, broad spectrum probiotic is optimum. For specific conditions, the dose may have to be increased to double or even triple the usual levels.\r\n\r\n<strong>Safety: </strong>\r\nIt is helpful to look for probiotics with a long history of use. Some probiotics have received a Natural Product Number (NPN), which informs consumers that the product has been reviewed by the Canadian Natural Health Products Directorate (NHPD) for quality and health claims. Look for the NPN number on the product label when selecting probiotics.\r\n\r\n<strong>Origin: </strong>\r\nProbiotics can come from human, animal, soil or plant origin. Human strains are most compatible with the human gut and can survive the stomach acid and bile salts.\r\n\r\n<strong>Reliability: </strong>\r\nProbiotics should meet or exceed their label guarantees of live cell count (CFU/g) at time of purchase and until expiration date. Probiotics are living microorganisms that live in little or no oxygen in the gut. They are sensitive to oxygen, moisture and heat. Production and packaging of probiotics should involve limiting exposure to oxygen by packaging in barrier packages and eliminating the oxygen by flushing with nitrogen. It is important to have low moisture in the probiotic capsule. Products should be protected from dramatic fluctuations in temperature.\r\n\r\n<strong>Production of natural antibiotics: </strong>\r\nSome probiotics can produce other helpful substances like bacteriocins that reduce the numbers of harmful bacteria (one example is acidophilin produced by Lactobacillus acidophilus DDS-1). Certain strains can produce hydrogen peroxide that helps to reduce Candida albicans, which is responsible for yeast overgrowth.\r\n\r\n<strong>Acid and Bile Resistance: </strong>\r\nMany probiotics are not able to survive the acid in the stomach and bile in the small intestine to reach the desired location in the gut (in some cases, fewer than 25% can make it through). Look for acid and bile resistant probiotics.\r\n\r\n<strong>Colonizers vs. transients: </strong>\r\nMany probiotics are not able to colonize in the gut and they provide health benefits only on their way through the gut. Colonizers take up residence in the intestines, and then multiply and continue to provide benefits when they reach their destination. Colonizers can multiply 100 to 200-fold so 5 billion will soon become 500 billion or more. Some products start with very large numbers of bacteria because often less than 25% even make it to the gut.\r\n\r\n<strong>Production of enzymes: </strong>\r\nSome probiotics are able to produce enzymes that aid in digestion — proteases, lipases, amylases, cellulase and lactase. Natural production of digestive enzymes declines with age in humans so look for probiotics that will produce additional enzymes.\r\n\r\n<strong>Individual Probiotic Needs:</strong>\r\nDairy-free, gluten-free, soy-free, corn-free, non- GMO, veggie capsules are all qualities important to some people. Make sure you read the label to find out if your probiotics meet your needs.', 'How To Choose A Probiotic?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '533-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:28:25', '2012-10-31 14:28:25', '', 533, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/533-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(541, 1, '2012-10-31 14:28:51', '2012-10-31 14:28:51', 'The cold days of winter can bring on the worst of moods for even the most optimistic of people. Certain foods and supplements can restore balance to the body and provide essential nutrients, uplifting mood from inside out. The known health benefits of probiotics are numerous. They are most commonly used to help alleviate digestive disorders, but that’s just the beginning. The beneficial bacteria have also been positively linked to lower cholesterol, prevention of allergies, liver disease, yeast infections and cancer. They also help to reduce stress and improve your mood.\r\n\r\nIn a recent study, human subjects were given a probiotic formulation every day for 30 days. The probiotic regimen alleviated psychological distress in all subjects. Researchers concluded: “Exposure to chronic stress could disrupt the balance of intestinal microbiota and induce various diseases. Therefore, whatever the stress level, daily intake of probiotics could prevent such an imbalance, and the improvement in symptoms among subjects with low to mild stress levels suggests the value of prophylactic intake of probiotics in terms of digestive comfort and general well-being.”\r\n\r\nStart Taking a Probiotic Today!\r\n\r\nIf you’re looking to improve your mood naturally, in addition to aiding your digestive system among other health benefits, consider trying a probiotic dietary supplement. Look for products that contain live cultures of the most common strains of gut-friendly bacteria: Lactobacillus acidophilus, Bifidobacterium longum and Bifidobacterium bifidum. Any reputable probiotic product must have published human clinical research to support its use, and the product label must identify the bacterial strains in the product.', 'Probiotics to the rescue!', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '535-revision-2', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:28:51', '2012-10-31 14:28:51', '', 535, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/535-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
