(552, 1, '2012-10-31 14:38:17', '2012-10-31 14:38:17', 'Question: I’ve been taking a 30 billion cfu/g probiotic and now I see there is a 70 billion cfu/g product. How much should I be taking and what is considered enough?\n\nDr. Know: That’s an excellent question and displays the confusion surrounding “potency” when it comes to probiotics. What you need to understand is that potency is strain specific. What this means is that each strain of a probiotic is effective at a specific potency.\n\nTo give you an example using E. coli, some strains (like E. coli O157:H7) can cause severe illness and even death if you consume extremely small amounts. Other strains of E. coli are harmless at much larger doses, and there are even strains of E. coli (like E. coli Nissel 1917) that are considered probiotics at a certain dose. This wide variation in activity within a bacterial species is exact why Health Canada requires all probiotic products to list strain identification. Just listing the species (like E. coli or L. acidophilus) is essentially meaningless.\n\nUsing Inno-Vite’s flagship probiotic (Lactobacillus acidophilus DDS-1) product to clarify: Lactobacillus indicates the genus, acidophilus indicates the species, and lastly DDS-1 indicates the strain.\n\nTo group all probiotic species and strains together and list and overall potency is like grouping all minerals together and thinking one dose applies to all. To illustrate how wrong this is, take calcium, for example: 1000 mg of calcium is considered a good therapeutic dose. However, the same 1000 mg dose is toxic if you’re talking chromium (where a dose of 0.2 mg would be sufficient).\n\nSo yes, some probiotics may require 70 billion cfu to be effective, if that’s what the clinical trails determined. Others strains only require a dose of 100 million cfu. So when you’re choosing a probiotic product, don’t be fooled by the marketing game that’s being played out on the retail shelves. What’s most important is that you choose a product that has clinical research to show a particular strain actually exerts a “health benefit to the host” (the definition of a probiotic, which only clinical trials can reveal), and don’t be tricked by unscientific marketing.\n\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at <a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com">dr.Know@inno-vite.com</a>.', 'Probiotics: How much do you actually need?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '527-revision-3', '', '', '2012-10-31 14:38:17', '2012-10-31 14:38:17', '', 527, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/527-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
