(586, 1, '2013-02-25 00:39:31', '2013-02-25 00:39:31', '<h2>Question:</h2>\r\nI’ve heard a lot about vitamin K for bone health, and more recently about cardiovascular health. What else is it good for?\r\n<h2>Dr. Know:</h2>\r\nThe last few years has seen calcium take a beating from media reports on some negative studies on this essential mineral. The positive in this is that it’s really raised awareness over vitamin K’s importance in calcium metabolism. Now, many people are taking these supplements for two ominous health conditions—osteoporosis and cardiovascular disease. As people jump on board in greater numbers, many such as you are asking, “what else does it do?” Like vitamin D, where we find an increasing number of health conditions that benefit from this, we’re starting to see a similar picture emerge with vitamin K.\r\n\r\nIn 2011, a study linked a deficiency (and most people are deficient in K) to potential deficits in cognitive function and learning abilities. Other research suggests that a deficiency may increase the risk of calcium kidney stones (nephrocalcin is a vitamin K-dependent protein found in the kidneys), and some other research show people with low levels have a higher risk of certain cancers. Topically (and Inno-Vite’s liquid formulations work great as a topical serum), it’s used frequently for rosacea.\r\n\r\nA more recent—and in my opinion, theoretical—use of topical vitamin K is for aesthetic reasons, where wrinkle prevention is the desired goal. So you can see there are already many uses, and as research continues into this vitamin, I’m confident we’ll find many more benefits.\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at <a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com.">dr.Know@inno-vite.com.</a>', 'Expert Advice - K for Kidneys', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'k-for-kidneys', '', '', '2013-02-25 03:58:43', '2013-02-25 03:58:43', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=586', 0, 'post', '', 0),
