(607, 1, '2013-02-25 00:52:02', '2013-02-25 00:52:02', '<h2>Question:</h2>\r\nI’ve heard a lot about vitamin K for bone health, and more recently about cardiovascular health. What else is it good for?\r\n<h2>Dr. Know:</h2>\r\nThe last few years has seen calcium take a beating from media reports on some negative studies on this essential mineral. The positive in this is that it’s really raised awareness over vitamin K’s importance in calcium metabolism. Now, many people are taking these supplements for two ominous health conditions—osteoporosis and cardiovascular disease. As people jump on board in greater numbers, many such as you are asking, “what else does it do?” Like vitamin D, where we find an increasing number of health conditions that benefit from this, we’re starting to see a similar picture emerge with vitamin K.\r\n\r\nIn 2011, a study linked a deficiency (and most people are deficient in K) to potential deficits in cognitive function and learning abilities. Other research suggests that a deficiency may increase the risk of calcium kidney stones (nephrocalcin is a vitamin K-dependent protein found in the kidneys), and some other research show people with low levels have a higher risk of certain cancers. Topically (and Inno-Vite’s liquid formulations work great as a topical serum), it’s used frequently for rosacea.\r\n\r\nA more recent—and in my opinion, theoretical—use of topical vitamin K is for aesthetic reasons, where wrinkle prevention is the desired goal. So you can see there are already many uses, and as research continues into this vitamin, I’m confident we’ll find many more benefits.\r\n\r\nYou can send questions to Lee Know at <a href="mailto:dr.Know@inno-vite.com.">dr.Know@inno-vite.com.</a>', 'K for Kidneys', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '586-revision-5', '', '', '2013-02-25 00:52:02', '2013-02-25 00:52:02', '', 586, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/586-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(609, 1, '2013-06-09 22:50:23', '2013-06-09 22:50:23', 'Difficulty in concentrating is a normal and periodic occurrence for most people. Fatigue can cause concentration problems in most people. Hormonal changes, such as those experienced during menopause or pregnancy can also affect how you think and concentrate.  Emotional problems can also influence an individual''s cognitive functions and thus impair concentration. Concentration problems, when present to an excessive degree, are also characteristic of certain physical and psychological conditions.\r\n\r\nProbably the most common causes of attention difficulties are related to lifestyle issues. There are a few basic requirements that most people need in order to have optimal concentration, such as proper sleep, regular meals, and a reasonably comfortable and distraction-free environment. If you are a student, these aspects are frequently missing from your life. Often away from home to study you may be lax in providing a reasonably structured lifestyle for yourself. Many students get inadequate sleep, and their living arrangements may make a reasonably quiet atmosphere difficult. It''s important to realize that your concentration span can vary tremendously depending on the type of task, your motivation to do the work, your interest in the subject, how tired or ill you''re feeling at that moment in time, other events in your life, etc. It''s not much use to try to force yourself to concentrate for X number of minutes or hours. Rather than struggle against your ability to concentrate, it''s essential to work with it.\r\n\r\nIf you find that your mind\r\nbegins to wander after 10 or 15 minutes of reading, then stop and take a 5 minute break. Get up and stretch, throw some cold water on your face, get a breath of fresh air, get a coffee and go back to work. Monitor your concentration instead of counting how many pages are left in the chapter. If you are having difficulties keeping your mind sharp and paying full attention, try adding some natural remedies to your daily diet. Keep your mind and body active with the uplifting properties of stimulating herbs and natural nutrients, but remember to use each one in moderation so as not to over-load your body.', 'Having Difficulty in Concentrating?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'having-difficulty-in-concentrating', '', '', '2013-06-09 22:50:45', '2013-06-09 22:50:45', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=609', 0, 'post', '', 0),
