(499, 1, '2012-08-23 20:14:34', '2012-08-23 20:14:34', '“People working evening shifts, irregular shifts, night shifts and rotating shifts are at an increased risk for heart attack and stroke,” a new study published in British Medical Journal suggests.\r\n\r\nTo look at the connection between heart attack, stroke and shift work, Dr. Daniel Hackam, a clinical pharmacologist at the Stroke Prevention &amp; Atherosclerosis Research Centre in London, Ont., and his group analyzed 34 studies that included more than 2 million people. After poring over the results of these studies, they concluded that shift work was associated with increased rates of vascular events such as heart attacks and ischemic strokes caused by lack of blood to the brain.\r\n\r\n"Given the commonness of shift work in modern industrialized nations, and industrializing nations, many heart attacks and strokes are likely directly attributable to the effects of shift work," said lead researcher Dr. Daniel Hackam.\r\nShift work disrupts our body clocks and can wreak havoc with work-life balance. Among the people in these studies, more than 17,000 had some kind of cardiovascular problem. More than 6,500 had heart attacks and almost 1,900 had strokes, the research showed.\r\n\r\nHackam''s team found that shift workers had a nearly 25% increased risk of having a cardiovascular problem, a 23% increased risk of a heart attack and a 5% increased risk of a stroke when compared to non-shift workers. People working night shifts had the highest risk of a coronary event (41%), they added.\r\n\r\n"Individuals with these types of work schedules should recognize the potential increase in risk for cardiovascular events and stroke, and take proactive steps to improve their cardiovascular health," Dr. Daniel Hackam stated.\r\n\r\nThe best way to lower the risk of heart attack and stroke associated with shift work is to keep the usual risk factors — such as blood pressure, cholesterol, weight and diabetes — under control, experts say.\r\n\r\n"Shift workers need to be vigilant about their cardiovascular health and get their cardiovascular risk factors checked on an annual basis through their health care provider (e.g. cholesterol, blood pressure, glucose, waist circumference)," Dr. Hackam advised.', 'Shift Work Takes Its Toll on Your Heart!', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'shift-work-takes-its-toll-on-your-heart', '', '', '2012-08-23 20:14:34', '2012-08-23 20:14:34', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=499', 0, 'post', '', 0);
