(515, 1, '2012-08-23 20:12:14', '2012-08-23 20:12:14', '<h2>Not all CoQ10 Ubiquinol products are created equally.</h2>\nWhen CoQ10 ubiquinol (the biologically active, reduced form of CoQ10) was commercially launched on a mass scale in 2007, very few people would have guessed it would change the landscape of coenzyme Q10 products and their efficacy. However, since then, study after study has shown that ubiquinol has incredible therapeutic effects that far exceed those obtained with CoQ10 ubiquinone (the standard, oxidized form of CoQ10).\n\nEven the most extraordinary therapeutic ingredient is useless if the body can’t absorb it, and bioavailability is one of the main limiting factors for many CoQ10 supplements. One of the primary reasons for ubiquinol’s superiority is its high absorption, which has been proven time after time in numerous studies.\n\nFurthermore, what many may not realize is that CoQ10 ubiquinol, as a molecule, is not new. Indeed, being the antioxidant and predominant circulating form of CoQ10, scientists have known about ubiquinol for decades. However, it was impossible to use in supplements since ubiquinol is highly unstable. It oxidizes immediately when exposed to oxygen (air), and this oxidation converts it to plain old, regular CoQ10 (ubiquinone), which studies suggest may not deliver the therapeutic benefits that ubiquinol does.\n\nThe primary manufacturer of ubiquinol is Kaneka, who painstakingly laboured for 10 years in research and development to get ubiquinol stable enough to use in supplements. However, that only guarantees that they can deliver ubiquinol as a raw material to a finished product manufacturer. How it’s handled after this has a significant impact on the quality of the finished product.\n\nThis presents a problem for finished products that consumers may find in a store. Plastic bottles and the gelatin surrounding softgel capsules allow for oxygen transmission. So, assuming the product was handled carefully and manufactured properly, the clock starts ticking as soon as the product rolls off the production line. Even products in glass bottles, which are impermeable to oxygen, have this problem unless flushed with nitrogen to remove the oxygen from the bottle, and even so, the clock starts ticking once the bottle is opened.\n\nSo what’s the solution to ensure the superior efficacy of ubiquinol at the time of ingestion by the consumer/patient? The secret is in a patented process. This unique process ensures that ubiquinol in the finished product stays as CoQ10 ubiquinol right through to the expiry date. While brands who license this patent have an extra cost to endure (licensing intellectual property seldom comes cheaply), it ensures the product is of high quality.\n\nIn the case of ubiquinol, you really do get what you pay for. While many brands claim their products are stable simply because everyone uses the same raw materials, the quality of the finished products can vary dramatically.\n\nAt Inno-Vite, we ensure that our consumers have access to the highest quality products possible. Providing discount products at the expense of quality has never been — and never will be — a consideration at Inno-Vite.\n\nInno-Vite’s Inno-Q-Nol line of CoQ10 ubiquinol products offer guaranteed stability through this exclusive patented process. (US Patent 6,740,338).', 'Ubiquinol vs. Ubiquinol', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '503-revision-2', '', '', '2012-08-23 20:12:14', '2012-08-23 20:12:14', '', 503, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/503-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
