(525, 1, '2012-08-23 20:10:22', '2012-08-23 20:10:22', '4 servings\r\n<h2>Ingredients:</h2>\r\n1/3 cup sugar plus additional for sprinkling\r\n5 oz bittersweet dark chocolate, chopped\r\n3 large egg yolks at room temperature\r\n6 large egg whites\r\nTopping: Raspberries or any seasonal fruit (optional)\r\nSpecial equipment: a 5 1/2- to 6-cup glass or ceramic soufflé dish\r\n<h2>Preparation:</h2>\r\nPreheat oven to 375°F. Generously butter soufflé dish and sprinkle with sugar, knocking out excess.\r\nMelt chocolate in a metal bowl set over a saucepan of barely simmering water, stirring occasionally until smooth. Remove bowl from heat and stir in yolks (mixture will stiffen).\r\n\r\nBeat whites with a pinch of salt in a large bowl with an electric mixer at medium speed until they just hold soft peaks. Add 1/3 cup sugar, a little at a time, continuing to beat at medium speed, then beat at high speed until whites just hold stiff peaks. Stir about 1 cup whites into chocolate mixture to lighten, then add mixture to remaining whites, folding gently but thoroughly.\r\n\r\nSpoon into glass or ceramic soufflé dish and run the end of your thumb around inside edge of soufflé dish (this will help soufflé rise evenly). Bake in middle of oven until puffed and crusted on top but still jiggly in center, 24 to 26 minutes. Decorate with your favorite fruit and serve immediately.\r\nBon Appétit!', 'Chocolate Soufflé', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '507-revision-4', '', '', '2012-08-23 20:10:22', '2012-08-23 20:10:22', '', 507, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/507-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(563, 1, '2012-12-17 03:35:10', '2012-12-17 03:35:10', 'Winter can be a blissful season for people of all ages. The beauty of a sparkly snowfall, the thrill of sports like skiing and skating, the reward of a delicious hot chocolate after a day of outdoor fun are winter delights we can all enjoy. But for all its glory, once a cold snap hits, our motivation to stay physically active plunges along with the temperature. By decreasing our physical activity, we''re essentially “hibernating” our hearts, which is not good for them. Instead of avoiding the cold and snow, get outside and Embrace the Season!\r\nTry a winter sport like ice-skating, snowboarding, hockey, or even sledding. Staying active will boost your energy, keep your spirits high and your heart healthy. Here are just a few ideas that you and your family can do to get those hearts pumping:\r\n<h2>Get Your Family Outside!</h2>\r\nWith the dramatic increase in childhood obesity, getting kids outside during the winter is perhaps more important than it''s ever been. As the days get shorter and the temperature drops, many children prefer staying indoors and become more inactive watching TV or playing on the computer. Try tobogganing, skiing, skating, snowboarding, building a snow man or walking the dog with them. Get your friends and neighbours to participate. Take turns hosting backyard winter playtime and provide kids with fun materials to build snowmen and snow forts. Capture the fun on film. Document your family''s fun on camera or video. Show them how happy they are once they get bundled up and moving. Let them be your little helper. Next time you shovel the front walkway, encourage your kids to lend a hand. Give them a child-size shovel and let them pitch in. They''ll feel valued and their health will be the better for it. Reward their workout. When the kids pile in the door with their healthy glow, reward them with a fun snack or a cup of hot chocolate.\r\n<h2>Shovel with care!</h2>\r\nAside from being a tedious task, shoveling can also be dangerous.The physical demands of shovelling combined with cold temperatures can pose fatal risks on the heart. By taking the following precautions, you will be doing your heart a favour. Warm up. Shovelling is just like any other form of exercise. It''s a good idea to start with some basic stretches before you begin. Avoid a full stomach. Be sure to digest your meals before picking up the shovel. A full stomach can cause strain on the heart during physical activity. Take a break. Giving yourself a break in the middle of vigorous shovelling is necessary for the muscles, especially for the heart muscle. Consult your doctor. If you are older, overweight, out of shape and/or have a history of heart disease in the family, seek expert advice from your doctor before picking up that shovel.', 'Smart ways to be heart-smart this winter', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'smart-ways-to-be-heart-smart-this-winter', '', '', '2012-12-17 03:35:22', '2012-12-17 03:35:22', '', 0, 'http://www.inno-vite.com/articles/?p=563', 0, 'post', '', 0);

